// Hand-written jr-high/high-school reading passages that OVERRIDE the auto-templated
// ones (matched by slug). Structure: Hook → Context → Key Idea → Example → Legacy.
// Facts are aligned to the prose so the 3-random-question generator still works.
// Being filled in batches; anything not here yet falls back to the auto passage.
window.HIST_AUTHORED = [
  { slug:'mahatma_gandhi', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'India', birthplace:'Porbandar', spouse:'Kasturba Gandhi', work:'satyagraha', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Mahatma Gandhi was a leader from India, which was ruled by the British Empire during much of his life. He was born in Porbandar in 1869 and later studied law in London. Gandhi first used peaceful protest while living in South Africa, where he fought unfair treatment of Indian people. When he returned to India, he became one of the most important leaders in India's struggle for independence from British rule. Gandhi believed in satyagraha, which means using truth, courage, and nonviolent resistance instead of violence. One famous example was the Salt March in 1930, when he walked with followers to protest a British tax on salt. He was married to Kasturba Gandhi, and his ideas later inspired civil rights leaders around the world." },

  { slug:'nelson_mandela', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'South Africa', birthplace:'Mvezo', work:'ending apartheid', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Nelson Mandela was a leader from South Africa, a country where unfair laws called apartheid separated people by the color of their skin. He was born in the village of Mvezo in 1918 and trained as a lawyer. Mandela joined the fight against apartheid, believing that Black South Africans deserved equal rights. Because he spoke out and helped organize protests, the government sent him to prison, where he stayed for 27 years. Instead of giving up, he became a symbol of hope around the world. When he was finally freed in 1990, he chose forgiveness over revenge, and in 1994 he became South Africa's first Black president — showing that patience and courage can defeat even the most powerful injustice." },

  { slug:'martin_luther_king_jr', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'United States', birthplace:'Atlanta', spouse:'Coretta Scott King', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Martin Luther King Jr. was a leader from the United States during a time when Black Americans were treated unfairly under segregation laws. He was born in Atlanta in 1929 and became a minister like his father. King believed that people could win equal rights through peaceful protest instead of violence, an idea he learned partly from Mahatma Gandhi. In 1963 he led the March on Washington and gave his famous 'I Have a Dream' speech, calling for people of all races to be judged by their character. He was married to Coretta Scott King, who continued his work after he was killed in 1968. His courage helped end segregation and inspired movements for fairness all over the world." },

  { slug:'abraham_lincoln', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Hodgenville', spouse:'Mary Todd Lincoln', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Abraham Lincoln was the sixteenth president of the United States during the most dangerous time in the nation's history. He was born in a log cabin near Hodgenville, Kentucky, in 1809 and taught himself to read by firelight. When Lincoln became president in 1861, several Southern states left the country to protect slavery, starting the Civil War. Lincoln fought to keep the nation together and, in 1863, issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared enslaved people in the rebelling states to be free. He was married to Mary Todd Lincoln, and he guided the country until the war was nearly won. Lincoln was assassinated in 1865, but he is remembered for holding the nation together and helping to end slavery." },

  { slug:'leonardo_da_vinci', facts:{ field:'artist', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Vinci', work:'the Mona Lisa', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Leonardo da Vinci was an artist and inventor from Italy during the Renaissance, a time when Europe rediscovered art and learning. He was born near the town of Vinci in 1452 and showed his talent for drawing at an early age. Leonardo believed that art and science belonged together, so he studied the human body, water, birds, and light to make his paintings more real. He is most famous for painting the Mona Lisa, whose mysterious smile still draws crowds today. In his notebooks he sketched flying machines and other inventions hundreds of years before they were built. Leonardo's endless curiosity made him a symbol of the creative, questioning spirit of the Renaissance." },

  { slug:'isaac_newton', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'Woolsthorpe', work:'the law of gravity', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Isaac Newton was a scientist from England who changed the way people understand the universe. He was born in the village of Woolsthorpe in 1643 and grew up curious about how things move. According to a famous story, watching an apple fall led Newton to wonder about the force that pulls objects toward the Earth. He explained this force with his law of gravity and also wrote three laws of motion that describe how everything from balls to planets moves. Newton's ideas became the foundation of physics and helped later scientists send rockets into space. He is remembered as one of the greatest scientific thinkers who ever lived." },

  { slug:'charles_darwin', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'Shrewsbury', work:'the theory of evolution', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Charles Darwin was a naturalist from England who studied plants, animals, and fossils. He was born in Shrewsbury in 1809 and, as a young man, sailed around the world on a ship called HMS Beagle. On islands like the Galápagos, Darwin noticed that animals of the same kind looked slightly different from place to place. This led him to the theory of evolution by natural selection — the idea that living things slowly change over many generations to fit their surroundings. He explained his findings in a book called On the Origin of Species, which surprised and even upset many people at the time. Today his work is a cornerstone of modern biology." },

  { slug:'william_shakespeare', facts:{ field:'playwright', country:'England', birthplace:'Stratford-upon-Avon', spouse:'Anne Hathaway', work:'Hamlet', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"William Shakespeare was a playwright and poet from England, often called the greatest writer in the English language. He was born in the town of Stratford-upon-Avon in 1564 and later moved to London, where he wrote and performed plays. Shakespeare understood people deeply, and his stories explore love, jealousy, power, and revenge in ways that still feel true today. He wrote about 37 plays, including Hamlet, Romeo and Juliet, and Macbeth, and even invented hundreds of new words. He was married to Anne Hathaway and had three children back in Stratford. Four hundred years later, his plays are still performed all over the world." },

  { slug:'cleopatra', facts:{ field:'pharaoh', country:'Egypt', birthplace:'Alexandria', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Cleopatra was the last pharaoh, or ruler, of ancient Egypt. She was born in the great city of Alexandria around 69 BCE, at a time when the powerful Roman Empire was growing nearby. Cleopatra was famous for her sharp mind and her ability to speak many languages, which helped her deal with foreign leaders. To protect Egypt's independence, she formed alliances with two of Rome's most powerful men, Julius Caesar and Mark Antony. In the end, Rome grew too strong, and after her death Egypt became part of the Roman Empire. Cleopatra is still remembered as one of history's most clever and legendary rulers." },

  { slug:'julius_caesar', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Rome', birthplace:'Rome', work:'the Roman calendar', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Julius Caesar was a general and ruler of ancient Rome whose choices changed history. He was born in Rome around 100 BCE and rose to power by winning wars and gaining the loyalty of his soldiers. Caesar conquered new lands for Rome and became so powerful that he was named dictator for life. He also reformed the calendar, creating a 365-day year that is the ancestor of the one we use today. Many Roman senators feared he had too much power, and in 44 BCE they assassinated him. His death led to years of struggle that ended the Roman Republic and began the Roman Empire." },

  { slug:'napoleon', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'France', birthplace:'Ajaccio', work:'the Napoleonic Code', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Napoleon Bonaparte was a general who became the emperor of France. He was born on the island of Corsica in 1769 and rose quickly through the army during the chaos of the French Revolution. A brilliant military leader, Napoleon conquered much of Europe and spread new ideas about law and government. He created the Napoleonic Code, a set of laws that treated citizens more equally and still influences many countries today. But his endless wars cost millions of lives, and after a terrible defeat he was finally beaten at the Battle of Waterloo in 1815. Napoleon remains one of history's most studied and debated leaders, admired for his genius and blamed for his ambition." },

  { slug:'confucius', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'China', birthplace:'Qufu', work:'the Analects', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Confucius was a teacher and philosopher from ancient China whose ideas shaped an entire culture. He was born in the town of Qufu around 551 BCE, during a time of war and disorder among Chinese states. Confucius believed that society would be peaceful if people treated each other with respect, honesty, and kindness, especially within families. He traveled from place to place teaching students, and his sayings were later collected in a book called the Analects. Chinese governments used his ideas about good behavior and fair leadership for more than two thousand years. Today Confucius is still honored as one of the most important thinkers in all of history." },

  { slug:'genghis_khan', facts:{ field:'conqueror', country:'Mongolia', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Genghis Khan was a warrior and ruler from Mongolia who built the largest connected land empire the world has ever seen. He was born around 1162 and had a hard childhood, uniting the scattered Mongol tribes into one powerful nation. Genghis Khan led fierce armies of skilled horsemen who conquered lands across Asia and into Europe. His conquests were extremely violent and cost the lives of huge numbers of people. Yet his empire also connected distant cultures, protected trade along the Silk Road, and allowed people to follow different religions. Genghis Khan is remembered as both a brutal conqueror and a leader who linked the ancient world together." },

  { slug:'christopher_columbus', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Genoa', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Christopher Columbus was an explorer, born in the Italian city of Genoa around 1451, who sailed for the kingdom of Spain. Most Europeans of his time did not know that two huge continents lay across the Atlantic Ocean. In 1492 Columbus led three ships west, hoping to reach Asia, and instead landed on islands in the Americas. His voyages opened lasting contact between Europe and the Americas, changing both worlds forever. But his arrival also brought terrible harm — disease, slavery, and violence — to the Indigenous peoples who already lived there. Columbus is remembered today as a bold sailor whose journeys had enormous and often tragic consequences." },

  { slug:'vincent_van_gogh', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Netherlands', birthplace:'Zundert', work:'The Starry Night', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Vincent van Gogh was a painter from the Netherlands whose bold colors helped shape modern art. He was born in the village of Zundert in 1853 and did not begin painting seriously until he was almost thirty. Van Gogh painted with thick, swirling brushstrokes and bright colors that showed his powerful emotions. His most famous painting, The Starry Night, shows a glowing night sky above a quiet town. Sadly, he struggled with poverty and mental illness and sold almost no paintings during his life. Only after his death did the world recognize his genius, and today his works are among the most loved and valuable paintings ever made." },

  { slug:'pablo_picasso', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Spain', birthplace:'Málaga', work:'Cubism', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Pablo Picasso was an artist from Spain who changed the rules of modern art. He was born in the city of Málaga in 1881 and could draw beautifully even as a child. As an adult, Picasso decided that art did not have to copy the real world exactly. With a friend, he helped invent a style called Cubism, which breaks objects into flat shapes seen from many angles at once. He also painted Guernica, a huge black-and-white picture that protests the horrors of war. Over his long life Picasso created tens of thousands of works and became one of the most famous and influential artists of all time." },

  { slug:'ludwig_van_beethoven', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Bonn', work:'the Ninth Symphony', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Ludwig van Beethoven was a composer from Germany whose music helped begin a bold new age of classical music. He was born in the city of Bonn in 1770 and became a brilliant pianist as a young man. Beethoven wrote powerful symphonies, sonatas, and concertos full of strong emotion and surprise. Astonishingly, he slowly lost his hearing, yet he kept composing — even writing his famous Ninth Symphony after he had become almost completely deaf. That symphony's 'Ode to Joy' celebrates friendship and hope among all people. Beethoven proved that great art can rise out of great struggle, and his music is still performed around the world today." },

  { slug:'rosa_parks', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Tuskegee', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Rosa Parks was a civil rights activist from the United States who helped change unfair laws with a single brave choice. She was born in Tuskegee, Alabama, in 1913, at a time when segregation forced Black Americans to use separate seats, schools, and services. In 1955, Parks refused to give up her bus seat to a white passenger in Montgomery, and she was arrested. Her stand sparked the Montgomery Bus Boycott, in which Black residents refused to ride the buses for over a year. The boycott helped launch the modern civil rights movement and made Rosa Parks a lasting symbol of quiet courage. Her example showed that ordinary people can help change history by standing up for what is right." },

  { slug:'frederick_douglass', facts:{ field:'abolitionist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Talbot County', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Frederick Douglass was a writer and speaker from the United States who fought to end slavery. He was born enslaved in Talbot County, Maryland, around 1818, and secretly taught himself to read even though it was against the law. As a young man, Douglass escaped to freedom in the North, where he began giving powerful speeches about the cruelty of slavery. He wrote books about his own life that convinced many people that slavery must end. During the Civil War, he urged President Lincoln to let Black men fight for the Union and for their own freedom. Frederick Douglass showed how education and courage could turn a person born into slavery into one of the greatest leaders in American history." },

  { slug:'harriet_tubman', facts:{ field:'abolitionist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Dorchester County', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Harriet Tubman was a hero of the fight against slavery in the United States. She was born enslaved in Dorchester County, Maryland, around 1822, and suffered greatly as a child. As a young woman, Tubman escaped to freedom in the North, but she did not stop there. She returned to the South again and again, secretly guiding many enslaved people to freedom along a network of safe houses called the Underground Railroad. During the Civil War she even served the Union army as a scout, nurse, and spy. Known for her bravery and cleverness, Harriet Tubman risked her life over and over so that others could be free." },

  { slug:'socrates', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Athens', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Socrates was a philosopher from the ancient Greek city of Athens, a place famous for its early experiments with democracy. He was born around 470 BCE and, unlike most famous thinkers, never wrote down his ideas. Instead, Socrates walked through the city asking people careful questions about big topics like justice, courage, and truth. This questioning method, now called the Socratic method, showed people how little they truly understood and pushed them to think for themselves. His challenges annoyed powerful men, and he was put on trial and sentenced to death. Yet his student Plato wrote down his conversations, and Socrates is still honored as a father of Western philosophy." },

  { slug:'plato', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Athens', work:'The Republic', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Plato was a philosopher from ancient Athens and one of the most important thinkers in history. He was born around 428 BCE and studied under the great questioner Socrates. After Socrates was put to death, Plato wrote down many of their conversations as 'dialogues' so their ideas would not be lost. In his book The Republic, Plato imagined what a perfectly just society and a wise leader might look like. He also founded a school called the Academy, one of the first universities in the Western world. Plato's ideas about truth, justice, and government have been studied for more than two thousand years." },

  { slug:'aristotle', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Stagira', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Aristotle was a philosopher and scientist from ancient Greece who tried to understand almost everything. He was born in the town of Stagira around 384 BCE and studied at Plato's Academy in Athens. Aristotle believed that people should learn by observing the real world, so he studied animals, weather, government, and the stars. He created systems for organizing knowledge, including the rules of logic that we still use to reason carefully. He even became the personal teacher of a young prince named Alexander, who would grow up to conquer much of the known world. For centuries afterward, scholars in Europe and the Middle East called Aristotle simply 'the Philosopher.'" },

  { slug:'archimedes', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Syracuse', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Archimedes was a mathematician and inventor from the ancient Greek city of Syracuse. He was born around 287 BCE and became famous for using math to explain how the physical world works. Archimedes studied levers and pulleys and reportedly said that, given a place to stand, he could move the whole Earth. According to legend, he discovered how to measure the volume of objects while taking a bath and shouted 'Eureka!' — meaning 'I found it!' He also designed clever machines to defend his city from Roman attack. His discoveries in geometry and engineering influenced science for nearly two thousand years." },

  { slug:'michelangelo', facts:{ field:'sculptor', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Caprese', work:'the statue of David', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Michelangelo was an artist from Italy and one of the greatest talents of the Renaissance. He was born in the village of Caprese in 1475 and showed astonishing skill as both a sculptor and a painter. From a single block of marble he carved the statue of David, a giant figure so lifelike that people could hardly believe it was stone. He also spent four years lying on his back to paint the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel in Rome, filling it with hundreds of figures. Michelangelo worked with fierce energy well into old age, always chasing perfection. His art still amazes millions of visitors every year." },

  { slug:'wolfgang_amadeus_mozart', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Austria', birthplace:'Salzburg', spouse:'Constanze Mozart', work:'The Magic Flute', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart was a composer from Austria and one of the greatest musical geniuses who ever lived. He was born in the city of Salzburg in 1756 and was a child prodigy, playing the piano and composing music before he was six years old. As a boy, he toured Europe performing for kings and queens. Mozart wrote more than 600 pieces of music, including symphonies, concertos, and operas such as The Magic Flute. He was married to Constanze Mozart, but he struggled with money and died young, at just 35. Even so, his beautiful, joyful music is still loved and performed all over the world." },

  { slug:'johann_sebastian_bach', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Eisenach', spouse:'Anna Magdalena Bach', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Johann Sebastian Bach was a composer and organist from Germany, considered one of the greatest musicians in history. He was born in the town of Eisenach in 1685 into a large family of musicians. Bach spent his life working for churches and courts, writing music for choirs, organs, and small orchestras. He was a master of counterpoint, weaving several melodies together so they fit like the gears of a clock. He was married to Anna Magdalena Bach, and several of his many children became composers too. Though he was not world-famous in his own time, Bach's music is now studied by nearly every serious musician." },

  { slug:'george_washington', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Virginia', spouse:'Martha Washington', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"George Washington was a general and the first president of the United States. He was born in the colony of Virginia in 1732, when America was still ruled by Britain. When the thirteen colonies rebelled, Washington was chosen to lead the ragged American army through the long and difficult Revolutionary War. His steady leadership helped the colonies win their independence. Afterward, he could have made himself a king, but instead he helped create a republic and served two terms as president before stepping down. He was married to Martha Washington, and he is often called the 'Father of His Country.'" },

  { slug:'benjamin_franklin', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'United States', birthplace:'Boston', work:'the lightning rod', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Benjamin Franklin was an inventor, writer, and statesman from the United States, famous for his endless curiosity. He was born in Boston in 1706 and became a successful printer before turning to science. In a famous experiment, Franklin flew a kite in a thunderstorm to study electricity, which led him to invent the lightning rod to protect buildings. He also invented bifocal glasses and a clever heating stove, and he never patented his ideas so everyone could use them. As a leader, he helped write the Declaration of Independence and won France's help during the American Revolution. Franklin showed how one curious mind could improve both science and society." },

  { slug:'thomas_jefferson', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Shadwell', work:'the Declaration of Independence', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Thomas Jefferson was a writer and the third president of the United States. He was born in Shadwell, Virginia, in 1743 and grew up loving books, science, and ideas. In 1776, Jefferson wrote most of the Declaration of Independence, including the famous words that 'all men are created equal.' As president, he doubled the size of the country by buying a huge region of land in the Louisiana Purchase. Yet Jefferson also enslaved many people, a painful contradiction with his own words about freedom. He is remembered as a brilliant thinker whose ideals shaped America even as his own life showed the nation's deep flaws." },

  { slug:'winston_churchill', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'England', work:'his wartime speeches', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Winston Churchill was the prime minister who led Britain through the darkest days of World War II. He was born in England in 1874 into a famous family and worked as a soldier and writer before entering politics. When Nazi Germany conquered much of Europe and bombed British cities, Churchill refused to surrender. His powerful wartime speeches, promising 'we shall never surrender,' helped keep his country's spirit alive. Working with the United States and the Soviet Union, Britain helped defeat Nazi Germany in 1945. Churchill's career included serious mistakes, but he is remembered above all for his courage and words during a time of great danger." },

  { slug:'franklin_d_roosevelt', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Hyde Park', spouse:'Eleanor Roosevelt', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Franklin D. Roosevelt, often called FDR, was the president who guided the United States through two enormous crises. He was born in Hyde Park, New York, in 1882 and, as an adult, was partly paralyzed by polio, yet he never stopped leading. When he became president in 1933, the country was trapped in the Great Depression, with millions out of work. Roosevelt created programs called the New Deal to give people jobs, food, and hope. Later he led the nation through most of World War II. He was married to Eleanor Roosevelt, a champion of human rights, and FDR is the only president ever elected four times." },

  { slug:'john_f_kennedy', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Brookline', spouse:'Jacqueline Kennedy', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"John F. Kennedy was the 35th president of the United States, serving during the tense years of the Cold War. He was born in Brookline, Massachusetts, in 1917 and became one of the youngest people ever elected president. Kennedy inspired the nation with his call to public service, asking Americans what they could do for their country. He faced a frightening standoff with the Soviet Union over missiles in Cuba and helped avoid a nuclear war. He also challenged the country to land a person on the Moon before the decade ended. He was married to Jacqueline Kennedy, and his life was cut short when he was assassinated in 1963." },

  { slug:'alexander_the_great', facts:{ field:'conqueror', country:'Macedonia', birthplace:'Pella', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Alexander the Great was a young king and conqueror from the ancient kingdom of Macedonia, in northern Greece. He was born in the city of Pella in 356 BCE and was taught by the philosopher Aristotle. Becoming king at just 20, Alexander led his army on an astonishing campaign, conquering the mighty Persian Empire and marching all the way to India. By the time he died at only 32, he ruled one of the largest empires the world had ever seen. Wherever he went, he spread Greek language, art, and ideas, blending them with the cultures he conquered. His empire soon broke apart, but his legend as a brilliant general has lasted for over two thousand years." },

  { slug:'joan_of_arc', facts:{ field:'soldier', country:'France', birthplace:'Domrémy', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Joan of Arc was a peasant girl who became a military hero of France during the Middle Ages. She was born in the village of Domrémy around 1412, while France was losing a long war against England. As a teenager, Joan believed that God was calling her to save her country, and she convinced the French leaders to let her join the army. Wearing armor, she inspired the soldiers and helped win important battles, turning the tide of the war. Captured by her enemies, she was put on trial and executed when she was only about 19. Centuries later she was made a saint, and today she is a national symbol of courage and faith." },

  { slug:'marco_polo', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Venice', work:'his book of travels', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Marco Polo was an explorer from the Italian city of Venice who traveled farther than almost any European of his time. He was born around 1254 and, as a teenager, set out with his father and uncle on a journey along the Silk Road to China. There he spent many years in the service of the powerful Mongol ruler Kublai Khan. When Marco Polo finally returned home, he described the riches and wonders of Asia in a famous book of travels. Many Europeans could hardly believe his stories of paper money, huge cities, and strange customs. His book made Europeans curious about the wider world and helped inspire later explorers." },

  { slug:'amelia_earhart', facts:{ field:'aviator', country:'United States', birthplace:'Atchison', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Amelia Earhart was a pilot from the United States who became one of the most famous women in aviation history. She was born in Atchison, Kansas, in 1897, when flying was brand new and considered too dangerous for women. Earhart fell in love with airplanes and set record after record, becoming the first woman to fly alone across the Atlantic Ocean. She used her fame to encourage women to chase careers once thought impossible for them. In 1937, while trying to fly all the way around the world, her plane vanished over the Pacific Ocean and was never found. Her courage and mysterious disappearance have made her a lasting legend." },

  { slug:'neil_armstrong', facts:{ field:'astronaut', country:'United States', birthplace:'Wapakoneta', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Neil Armstrong was an American astronaut who became the first human being to walk on the Moon. He was born in Wapakoneta, Ohio, in 1930 and grew up fascinated by flight, becoming a test pilot and then an astronaut. During the Cold War, the United States and the Soviet Union were racing to reach the Moon first. In July 1969, Armstrong and his crew flew the Apollo 11 mission, and he stepped onto the Moon's surface with the words, 'That's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.' Millions of people around the world watched the landing on television. His calm courage made him a symbol of what humans can achieve when they dream big." },

  { slug:'charles_dickens', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'Portsmouth', spouse:'Catherine Dickens', work:'A Christmas Carol', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Charles Dickens was one of the most beloved writers in the history of England. He was born in Portsmouth in 1812, and as a boy his family fell into debt, forcing him to leave school and work in a factory. These hard experiences taught Dickens to care deeply about poor and struggling people. He turned his observations into famous novels such as Oliver Twist and A Christmas Carol, whose characters felt so real that readers loved and hated them. He was married to Catherine Dickens and had ten children. Through his stories, Dickens made his readers laugh, cry, and think about how society treated its poorest members." },

  { slug:'anne_frank', title:'Anne Frank', emoji:'✍️', img:'anne_frank.jpg', region:'W', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Frankfurt', work:'her diary', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Anne Frank was a Jewish girl whose diary became one of the most important books to come out of World War II. She was born in Frankfurt, Germany, in 1929, but her family fled to the Netherlands to escape the Nazis, who persecuted Jewish people. When the danger grew, the Franks hid in a secret set of rooms behind Anne's father's office in Amsterdam. For two years, Anne kept a diary about her fears, hopes, and dreams while in hiding. She wrote that despite everything, she still believed people were truly good at heart. After she died in a concentration camp, her diary was published, giving the world an unforgettable window into history through a young girl's eyes." },

  { slug:'hokusai', facts:{ field:'artist', country:'Japan', birthplace:'Edo', work:'The Great Wave', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Hokusai was a Japanese artist famous for his beautiful and dramatic woodblock prints. He was born in the city of Edo, now called Tokyo, in 1760, during a peaceful period in Japan's history. Hokusai created his most famous image, The Great Wave off Kanagawa, which shows a towering blue wave curling over tiny boats with Mount Fuji in the distance. He made tens of thousands of artworks and never stopped trying to improve, saying he only began to truly understand nature in his seventies. When his prints reached Europe, they amazed painters and influenced modern art. Today The Great Wave is one of the most recognized images in the world." },

  { slug:'frida_kahlo', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Mexico', birthplace:'Coyoacán', spouse:'Diego Rivera', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Frida Kahlo was a painter from Mexico known for her bold, colorful, and deeply personal art. She was born in Coyoacán, near Mexico City, in 1907, and a terrible bus accident as a teenager left her in pain for the rest of her life. While recovering, Kahlo began to paint, especially self-portraits that showed both her suffering and her strength. Her paintings were filled with Mexican colors, symbols, and traditions, and she wore proud, traditional clothing. She was married to the famous muralist Diego Rivera, and their stormy relationship shaped much of her work. Today Frida Kahlo is celebrated around the world as a symbol of courage and Mexican culture." },

  { slug:'sun_tzu', facts:{ field:'general', country:'China', work:'The Art of War', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Sun Tzu was an ancient Chinese general and thinker, traditionally believed to have written a famous book called The Art of War. He is said to have lived around 500 BCE, during a time when Chinese states often fought one another. The Art of War teaches that the smartest leaders win by careful planning, discipline, and understanding both themselves and their opponents. Sun Tzu argued that the greatest victory is to win without even having to fight. His ideas about strategy have been studied for more than two thousand years, not just by soldiers but also by business leaders and coaches. Few short books have had such a long and wide influence." },

  { slug:'sacagawea', facts:{ field:'guide', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Sacagawea was a young Shoshone woman who played a vital role in exploring the American West. She was born around 1788 and, as a teenager, joined the famous Lewis and Clark expedition in 1805. The explorers were mapping a huge stretch of North America that was unknown to them, and Sacagawea guided them and translated with Native American nations along the way. She traveled thousands of difficult miles while carrying her baby son on her back. Her presence also signaled to other tribes that the group came in peace. Sacagawea is remembered as a symbol of the important, often overlooked roles Native Americans played in the nation's history." },

  { slug:'rumi', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'Persia', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Rumi was a Persian poet and spiritual teacher whose words are still read by millions of people today. He was born in the early 1200s in a region of Central Asia and later settled in what is now Turkey. Rumi was a respected scholar until he met a wandering mystic who changed his life and filled him with a deep love of God and of all people. From then on, Rumi poured his feelings into thousands of poems about love, kindness, and the search for meaning. His most famous work is a long poem called the Masnavi. Centuries later, Rumi's gentle, hopeful poetry has made him one of the best-selling poets in the world." },

  { slug:'laozi', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'China', work:'the Dao De Jing', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Laozi, whose name means 'Old Master,' was an ancient Chinese thinker traditionally seen as the founder of Daoism. Little is known for certain about his life, and some scholars wonder whether he was one person or several. He is said to have lived around the 6th century BCE and to have written a short, poetic book called the Dao De Jing. Its verses teach people to live in harmony with nature, to stay humble, and to avoid forcing things. Laozi believed that the wisest leaders rule gently and quietly, letting people live in peace. His ideas shaped Chinese philosophy, religion, art, and government for thousands of years." },

  { slug:'qin_shi_huang', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'China', work:'the Terracotta Army', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Qin Shi Huang was the first emperor to unite all of China under a single ruler. He was born around 259 BCE and, through fierce warfare, conquered rival kingdoms to form one empire. To hold his huge realm together, he standardized China's writing, money, and measurements, and began connecting walls into an early version of the Great Wall. But Qin Shi Huang ruled harshly, punishing those who disagreed and forcing many people to labor on his projects. Obsessed with living forever, he had a vast underground tomb built, guarded by the Terracotta Army — thousands of life-sized clay soldiers. His empire fell soon after his death, yet he had shaped the idea of a united China that still lasts today." },

  { slug:'nefertiti', facts:{ field:'queen', country:'Egypt', spouse:'Akhenaten', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Nefertiti was a powerful queen of ancient Egypt, remembered for her beauty and her influence. She lived in the 1300s BCE and was married to the pharaoh Akhenaten. Together they made a bold and unusual change, leading Egypt to worship a single sun god instead of its many traditional gods. Nefertiti appears in ancient artwork standing beside her husband as an equal, which was rare for a queen. A famous painted statue of her head, discovered by archaeologists, has made her one of the most recognized faces from the ancient world. Much about her life remains a mystery, which only adds to her fame." },

  { slug:'louis_pasteur', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'France', birthplace:'Dole', work:'pasteurization', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Louis Pasteur was a scientist from France whose discoveries saved countless lives. He was born in the town of Dole in 1822 and became curious about the tiny living things called microbes, or germs. Pasteur proved that germs, not bad air, cause many diseases and cause food to spoil. He invented a process now called pasteurization, which gently heats milk and other liquids to kill harmful germs and keep them safe to drink. He also developed vaccines that protected people and animals from deadly illnesses like rabies. Pasteur's work created the science of microbiology and changed medicine, food safety, and public health forever." },

  { slug:'alexander_fleming', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Scotland', work:'penicillin', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Alexander Fleming was a scientist from Scotland who made one of the most important discoveries in medicine — almost by accident. He was born in 1881 and worked as a doctor studying bacteria, the germs that cause many infections. In 1928, Fleming returned from vacation to find that a mold had grown on one of his dishes and killed the bacteria around it. He realized the mold produced a germ-fighting substance, which he named penicillin. Penicillin became the first true antibiotic, a medicine that cures infections that once killed people. Fleming's lucky discovery, carefully studied, has saved millions of lives around the world." },

  { slug:'michael_faraday', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'London', work:'the electric motor', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Michael Faraday was a scientist from England who helped unlock the secrets of electricity. He was born in London in 1791 into a poor family and had very little schooling. Working first as a bookbinder, Faraday read the science books he was binding and taught himself. He went on to discover that a moving magnet can create an electric current, a principle that led him to build the first electric motor and generator. These inventions made it possible to produce and use electricity on a large scale. Though he never had a fancy education, Faraday became one of the greatest experimental scientists in history." },

  { slug:'nicolaus_copernicus', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'Poland', birthplace:'Toruń', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Nicolaus Copernicus was an astronomer from Poland who dared to rethink the entire universe. He was born in the city of Toruń in 1473, at a time when nearly everyone believed the Earth stood still at the center of everything. After years of careful study, Copernicus concluded that the Earth and the other planets actually orbit the Sun. This idea was so shocking that he waited until the end of his life to publish it. His book quietly began a scientific revolution that would later be proven by astronomers like Galileo and Kepler. Copernicus showed that even the oldest, most trusted beliefs should be tested against careful observation." },

  { slug:'johannes_kepler', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Weil der Stadt', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Johannes Kepler was an astronomer and mathematician from Germany who discovered how the planets move. He was born in the town of Weil der Stadt in 1571 and had poor eyesight, yet he loved studying the sky. Using years of careful measurements, Kepler figured out that planets travel around the Sun in stretched circles called ellipses, not perfect circles as people had believed. He described this and other patterns in three famous laws of planetary motion. His discoveries helped prove that the Earth orbits the Sun and later helped Isaac Newton explain gravity. Kepler showed the power of combining careful math with patient observation." },

  { slug:'stephen_hawking', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'Oxford', work:'A Brief History of Time', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Stephen Hawking was a physicist from England who explored the biggest mysteries of the universe. He was born in Oxford in 1942 and became fascinated by space, time, and black holes. As a young man, Hawking was diagnosed with a disease called ALS that slowly paralyzed his body, yet his mind stayed sharp and he kept working for decades. Using a computer and a voice machine to communicate, he made major discoveries about black holes and the beginning of the universe. His book A Brief History of Time explained these giant ideas to ordinary readers and became a worldwide bestseller. Hawking showed that curiosity and determination can overcome even the hardest challenges." },

  { slug:'jane_goodall', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'London', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Jane Goodall is a scientist from England famous for her study of wild chimpanzees. She was born in London in 1934 and loved animals from the time she was a child. In 1960 she traveled to a forest in Tanzania, in Africa, to observe chimpanzees up close, something few scientists had done. Goodall discovered that chimpanzees make and use tools and have close family bonds, which changed how people understand animals. Later she became a global leader in protecting wildlife and the environment, encouraging young people to take action. Her patient work in the forest turned her into one of the most respected scientists in the world." },

  { slug:'ferdinand_magellan', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Portugal', work:'the first voyage around the world', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Ferdinand Magellan was an explorer from Portugal who led the first expedition to sail all the way around the world. He was born around 1480 and sailed for Spain, hoping to reach the rich Spice Islands by traveling west. In 1519 he set out with five ships across the Atlantic and found a passage at the tip of South America into a huge, calm ocean he named the Pacific. The voyage was long and brutal, and Magellan himself was killed in a battle in the Philippines before it ended. But one of his ships completed the journey, proving for the first time that the world could be circled by sea. His voyage forever changed how people understood the size and shape of the Earth." },

  { slug:'james_cook', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'England', birthplace:'Marton', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"James Cook was an explorer and mapmaker from England who charted large parts of the Pacific Ocean. He was born in the village of Marton in 1728 and rose from humble beginnings to become a skilled ship captain. On three long voyages, Cook mapped the coasts of New Zealand and eastern Australia and reached many Pacific islands with great accuracy. He was one of the first captains to keep his sailors healthy on long voyages by improving their diet. His journeys brought European contact to many Pacific peoples, which had lasting and sometimes harmful effects on them. Cook is remembered as a brilliant navigator whose maps guided sailors for generations." },

  { slug:'queen_victoria', facts:{ field:'queen', country:'England', birthplace:'London', spouse:'Prince Albert', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Queen Victoria ruled the United Kingdom for more than 60 years, one of the longest reigns in British history. She was born in London in 1819 and became queen at just 18 years old. During her reign, called the Victorian era, Britain grew into a huge empire and led the world in industry, trade, and invention. Victoria was married to Prince Albert, and after he died she wore black mourning clothes for the rest of her life. Her name came to stand for a whole age of factories, railways, and strict manners. When she died in 1901, she had ruled over a quarter of the world's people." },

  { slug:'catherine_the_great', facts:{ field:'empress', country:'Russia', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Catherine the Great was an empress who ruled Russia for over 30 years and made it a major European power. She was born a German princess in 1729 and married into the Russian royal family. When her husband proved to be a weak and unpopular ruler, Catherine seized the throne for herself. As empress, she expanded Russia's borders, built schools and hospitals, and welcomed the new ideas of the Enlightenment. She loved art and collected paintings that became one of the world's greatest museums. Yet her glittering reign was also built on the harsh system of serfdom, which kept most Russians poor and unfree." },

  { slug:'charlemagne', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'France', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Charlemagne, whose name means 'Charles the Great,' was a king who united much of western Europe during the Middle Ages. He was born around 748 and became king of the Franks, a people living in what is now France and Germany. Through many wars, Charlemagne built a large empire and, in the year 800, was crowned emperor by the pope. He encouraged learning, ordered the building of schools, and helped preserve ancient books during a time of disorder. His empire did not last long after his death, but it planted the seeds of later European nations. Charlemagne is often called the 'Father of Europe.'" },

  { slug:'theodore_roosevelt', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'New York City', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Theodore Roosevelt was the energetic 26th president of the United States. He was born in New York City in 1858 and was a sickly child who built up his strength through exercise and adventure. As president in the early 1900s, Roosevelt fought against powerful companies that treated workers and customers unfairly. He loved the outdoors and protected millions of acres of forests, creating many national parks and monuments. He also helped the United States become a stronger power on the world stage. Bold and larger-than-life, Roosevelt showed how a president could use the office to push for big changes." },

  { slug:'simo_n_boli_var', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Venezuela', birthplace:'Caracas', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Simón Bolívar was a general and leader who helped free much of South America from Spanish rule. He was born into a wealthy family in Caracas, Venezuela, in 1783, when Spain controlled most of the continent. Inspired by ideas of liberty, Bolívar led armies across mountains and jungles in a long fight for independence. His victories helped create several new nations, including Venezuela, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Bolivia, which was named in his honor. He dreamed of uniting these countries into one strong republic, but they soon split apart. Known as 'El Libertador' — the Liberator — Bolívar remains a hero across Latin America." },

  { slug:'jane_austen', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'Steventon', work:'Pride and Prejudice', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Jane Austen was an English writer whose novels are still loved more than 200 years after she wrote them. She was born in the village of Steventon in 1775, the daughter of a country clergyman. Austen wrote sharp, funny stories about young women, families, money, and marriage in the England of her time. Her most famous novel, Pride and Prejudice, follows the clever Elizabeth Bennet as she navigates love and society. Austen published her books without her name on them, and few people knew who the author was during her life. Today she is celebrated as one of the greatest and wittiest novelists in the English language." },

  { slug:'leo_tolstoy', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Russia', spouse:'Sophia Tolstaya', work:'War and Peace', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Leo Tolstoy was a Russian writer often ranked among the greatest novelists of all time. He was born in 1828 on his family's country estate and grew up as a wealthy nobleman. Tolstoy wrote enormous, detailed novels that explored love, war, family, and the meaning of life. His masterpiece War and Peace follows many characters through Russia's struggle against Napoleon's invasion. He was married to Sophia Tolstaya, who helped copy his huge manuscripts by hand. Later in life Tolstoy gave up his riches and preached simple living and nonviolence, ideas that influenced leaders like Mahatma Gandhi." },

  { slug:'homer', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'Greece', work:'the Odyssey', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Homer is the ancient Greek poet believed to have created two of the most famous stories in Western literature. He is thought to have lived around the 8th century BCE, though so little is known about him that some wonder if he was a single person at all. Homer is credited with the Iliad, about the great Trojan War, and the Odyssey, about the hero Odysseus and his long, adventurous journey home. These epic poems were first performed out loud, passed down by memory before they were written. They are filled with gods, monsters, heroes, and lessons about courage and cleverness. For nearly three thousand years, Homer's stories have inspired writers, artists, and readers." },

  { slug:'maya_angelou', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'United States', birthplace:'St. Louis', work:'I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Maya Angelou was an American poet, writer, and civil rights activist. She was born in St. Louis in 1928 and endured a difficult and painful childhood in the segregated South. As an adult, Angelou worked as a dancer, singer, and actress before becoming a writer. Her book I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings tells the true story of her early life and became one of the most important works in American literature. She wrote with honesty about racism, hardship, and hope, and read a poem at a president's inauguration. Angelou's warm, powerful words continue to inspire people to face pain with dignity and courage." },

  { slug:'claude_monet', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'France', birthplace:'Paris', work:'Impressionism', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Claude Monet was a French painter who helped start a whole new style of art called Impressionism. He was born in Paris in 1840 and loved painting outdoors, directly from nature. Instead of making every detail sharp and exact, Monet used quick, loose brushstrokes to capture the changing light and color of a moment. One of his paintings, titled Impression, Sunrise, gave the Impressionist movement its name. He often painted the same scene — like his garden's water lilies — many times to show how it looked at different times of day. Monet's fresh, colorful way of seeing the world changed the course of modern art." },

  { slug:'mao_zedong', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'China', birthplace:'Shaoshan', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Mao Zedong was the leader who founded the People's Republic of China in 1949. He was born in the village of Shaoshan in 1893 and became a leader of the Chinese Communist Party. After a long civil war, Mao and his followers took control of China and reshaped the country according to communist ideas. He aimed to end old inequalities, but his programs, such as the Great Leap Forward and the Cultural Revolution, led to famine, chaos, and the deaths of millions of people. Mao remains a hugely important and deeply controversial figure. His decisions transformed China and still shape the country today." },

  { slug:'ashoka', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'India', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Ashoka was an emperor of ancient India who ruled one of the largest empires in the region's history. He was born around 304 BCE and, early in his reign, expanded his empire through brutal warfare. After a terrible battle that killed and displaced huge numbers of people, Ashoka was filled with regret and changed his ways completely. He embraced Buddhism and its message of peace, kindness, and respect for all living things. Ashoka had his new ideals carved onto stone pillars across his empire and built hospitals and roads for his people. He is remembered as a conqueror who chose compassion over cruelty." },

  { slug:'gautama_buddha', facts:{ field:'teacher', country:'India', birthplace:'Lumbini', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Gautama Buddha was a spiritual teacher whose ideas grew into the religion of Buddhism. He was born a prince named Siddhartha around the 5th century BCE, in Lumbini, in what is now Nepal. Living in a palace, he was shielded from suffering, but when he finally saw sickness, old age, and death, he left his comfortable life to search for answers. After years of meditation, he reached a deep understanding, or 'enlightenment,' and became known as the Buddha, meaning 'the Awakened One.' He taught that people can find peace by letting go of greed and treating others with compassion. His teachings spread across Asia and are followed by millions of people today." },

  { slug:'saladin', facts:{ field:'sultan', country:'Egypt', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Saladin was a Muslim sultan and general who became a legendary leader during the time of the Crusades. He was born around 1137 and rose to rule Egypt and Syria, uniting many Muslim lands. During the Crusades, European Christian armies fought to control the holy city of Jerusalem. In 1187 Saladin recaptured Jerusalem, and unlike many conquerors of his time, he treated the defeated people with unusual mercy. Even his enemies, including the English king Richard the Lionheart, respected his honor and generosity. Saladin is remembered across the world as a symbol of courage, wisdom, and fairness." },

  { slug:'cyrus_the_great', facts:{ field:'king', country:'Persia', work:'the Persian Empire', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Cyrus the Great was the king who founded the mighty Persian Empire in the 6th century BCE. He was born in the region of Persia, in what is now Iran, and through skillful leadership conquered many neighboring lands. At its height, his empire stretched across much of the ancient Middle East, making it the largest the world had yet seen. What set Cyrus apart was how he ruled: he allowed conquered peoples to keep their own religions and customs. He famously freed the Jewish people from captivity and let them return home. For his fairness, Cyrus is remembered as one of the wisest rulers of the ancient world." },

  { slug:'ramesses_ii', facts:{ field:'pharaoh', country:'Egypt', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Ramesses II, often called Ramesses the Great, was one of the most powerful pharaohs of ancient Egypt. He ruled for an astonishing 66 years during the 1200s BCE. Ramesses led his armies in famous battles and signed one of the earliest known peace treaties in history. He was also a great builder, covering Egypt with temples, statues, and monuments carved with his name. His huge temple at Abu Simbel, guarded by four giant statues of himself, still amazes visitors today. Because he ruled so long and left so many monuments, Ramesses II became a symbol of Egypt's golden age of power." },

  { slug:'tutankhamun', facts:{ field:'pharaoh', country:'Egypt', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Tutankhamun was a pharaoh of ancient Egypt who is famous today mostly because of his tomb. Often called 'King Tut,' he became pharaoh as a young boy around 1332 BCE and died when he was only about 18. During his short reign, he helped restore Egypt's old gods after his father had tried to change the religion. For thousands of years he was almost forgotten, until in 1922 archaeologists discovered his tomb still full of treasure. Inside they found golden jewelry, chariots, and his famous golden burial mask. The dazzling discovery made this once-minor king one of the most famous names from ancient Egypt." },

  { slug:'sitting_bull', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Sitting Bull was a respected leader of the Lakota Sioux people in North America. He was born around 1831, at a time when the United States was pushing Native American nations off their traditional lands. A brave warrior and a holy man, Sitting Bull refused to give up the freedom and land of his people. In 1876 he helped lead the defeat of U.S. soldiers at the Battle of the Little Bighorn. Though he was eventually forced onto a reservation, he never stopped defending his people's rights and traditions. Sitting Bull is remembered as a powerful symbol of Native American resistance and dignity." },

  { slug:'diego_rivera', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Mexico', birthplace:'Guanajuato', spouse:'Frida Kahlo', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Diego Rivera was a Mexican painter famous for his enormous wall paintings, called murals. He was born in the city of Guanajuato in 1886 and studied art in Europe before returning to Mexico. Rivera believed that art should belong to everyone, not just the rich, so he covered the walls of public buildings with huge, colorful scenes. His murals told the story of Mexico's history and celebrated its workers, farmers, and native peoples. He was married to the painter Frida Kahlo, and together they became one of the most famous couples in art. Rivera's bold public art helped shape Mexican identity and inspired mural painters around the world." },

  { slug:'louis_armstrong', facts:{ field:'musician', country:'United States', birthplace:'New Orleans', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Louis Armstrong was an American musician who helped make jazz one of the most popular kinds of music in the world. He was born in New Orleans in 1901 and grew up in great poverty, learning to play the cornet as a boy. Armstrong became a dazzling trumpet player and singer, known for his warm, gravelly voice and his joyful, inventive solos. He turned jazz into a music where a single performer could shine, changing the way musicians play. Songs like 'What a Wonderful World' made him beloved around the globe. As one of the first Black entertainers to win worldwide fame, Armstrong opened doors for many artists who followed." },

  { slug:'elvis_presley', facts:{ field:'singer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Tupelo', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Elvis Presley was an American singer often called the 'King of Rock and Roll.' He was born in Tupelo, Mississippi, in 1935 and grew up loving gospel, blues, and country music. In the 1950s, Elvis blended these styles into an exciting new sound and combined it with wild dance moves that thrilled young fans. His energetic performances and good looks made him one of the first true superstars of the television age. Songs like 'Hound Dog' and 'Jailhouse Rock' became huge hits. Elvis helped make rock and roll a worldwide sensation and remains one of the most famous entertainers in history." },

  { slug:'fre_de_ric_chopin', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Poland', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Frédéric Chopin was a composer and pianist from Poland, famous for his beautiful piano music. He was born near Warsaw in 1810 and was a child prodigy who could compose music before he was ten. As a young man he moved to Paris, France, where he became a celebrated performer and teacher. Chopin wrote almost all of his music for the piano, filling it with deep emotion, delicate melodies, and Polish folk rhythms. Though his health was fragile and he died young, his pieces are still played in concert halls everywhere. Chopin showed that the piano alone could express a whole world of feeling." },

  { slug:'pyotr_ilyich_tchaikovsky', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Russia', birthplace:'Votkinsk', work:'The Nutcracker', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky was a composer from Russia whose dramatic, emotional music is loved around the world. He was born in the town of Votkinsk in 1840 and trained as a lawyer before deciding to devote his life to music. Tchaikovsky wrote sweeping symphonies, concertos, and operas, but he is best known for his ballets. His ballet The Nutcracker is performed every winter for holiday audiences everywhere. He filled his music with soaring melodies that could sound joyful or heartbreaking. Tchaikovsky helped Russian classical music win respect and admiration all over the world." },

  { slug:'rembrandt', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Netherlands', birthplace:'Leiden', work:'The Night Watch', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Rembrandt was a painter from the Netherlands, considered one of the greatest artists of all time. He was born in the city of Leiden in 1606, during a golden age of Dutch art and trade. Rembrandt became a master of light and shadow, making his paintings glow as if lit by real candles. His huge group portrait, The Night Watch, is one of the most famous paintings in the world. He also painted many honest self-portraits, showing his own face aging over the years. Even after fame and money slipped away later in his life, Rembrandt kept painting works that still move people today." },

  { slug:'raphael', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Urbino', work:'The School of Athens', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Raphael was an Italian painter and one of the brightest stars of the Renaissance. He was born in the town of Urbino in 1483 and showed such talent that he was famous while still young. Raphael's paintings are admired for their grace, balance, and gentle beauty. In Rome, he painted a masterpiece called The School of Athens, showing the great thinkers of ancient Greece gathered together. He worked alongside other giants of the age, including Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo. Raphael died at just 37, but his harmonious art influenced painters for hundreds of years." },

  { slug:'voltaire', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'France', birthplace:'Paris', work:'Candide', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Voltaire was a French writer and philosopher and one of the leading thinkers of the Enlightenment. He was born in Paris in 1694 and became famous for his sharp wit and fearless opinions. Voltaire used humor and clever stories to attack cruelty, unfairness, and the abuse of power. His short novel Candide pokes fun at people who insist that everything happens for the best. He strongly defended freedom of speech and freedom of religion, sometimes getting himself thrown in prison or exiled. Voltaire's ideas helped inspire revolutions and shaped modern ideas about liberty and tolerance." },

  { slug:'rene_descartes', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'France', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"René Descartes was a French philosopher and mathematician often called the father of modern philosophy. He was born in France in 1596 and lived during a time when science was beginning to challenge old beliefs. Descartes wanted to build knowledge on a foundation that could not be doubted. He decided that the one thing he could be sure of was that he was thinking, which led to his famous saying, 'I think, therefore I am.' In mathematics, he connected algebra and geometry, an idea still taught in schools today. Descartes taught people to question everything and to reason carefully from first principles." },

  { slug:'immanuel_kant', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Königsberg', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Immanuel Kant was a German philosopher whose ideas shaped modern thinking about knowledge and right and wrong. He was born in the city of Königsberg in 1724 and lived such a regular life that neighbors said they could set their clocks by his daily walk. Kant asked deep questions about how the human mind understands the world. He argued that people should act only in ways they would want everyone else to act, a rule about fairness and duty. His writing is famously difficult, but its influence on philosophy is enormous. Kant is remembered as one of the most important thinkers of the Enlightenment." },

  { slug:'karl_marx', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Trier', work:'The Communist Manifesto', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Karl Marx was a German philosopher and economist whose ideas changed history. He was born in the city of Trier in 1818, during the rise of factories and the Industrial Revolution. Marx studied how societies are shaped by who owns the factories, land, and money. He argued that workers were treated unfairly by the wealthy owners and predicted that workers would one day rise up. With his friend Friedrich Engels, he wrote The Communist Manifesto, calling for a new kind of society. Marx's ideas, called communism, later inspired revolutions and governments across the world and are still debated today." },

  { slug:'adam_smith', facts:{ field:'economist', country:'Scotland', birthplace:'Kirkcaldy', work:'The Wealth of Nations', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Adam Smith was a thinker from Scotland often called the father of modern economics. He was born in the town of Kirkcaldy in 1723 and became a professor who studied how people trade, work, and grow wealthy. In his famous book The Wealth of Nations, Smith explained how, in a free market, people pursuing their own interests can end up helping society as a whole. He described this hidden force as an 'invisible hand.' His ideas encouraged free trade and shaped how governments and businesses think about money. More than 200 years later, students still study Adam Smith to understand how economies work." },

  { slug:'miguel_de_cervantes', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Spain', work:'Don Quixote', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Miguel de Cervantes was a Spanish writer who created one of the first and greatest novels in the world. He was born in Spain in 1547 and lived an adventurous, difficult life, even spending years as a captive after being taken by pirates. Later he wrote Don Quixote, the funny and touching story of a man who reads too many tales of knights and sets off on his own foolish adventures. The book gently makes fun of its dreaming hero while also celebrating his big heart. Don Quixote is often called the first modern novel. Cervantes is honored as the greatest writer in the Spanish language." },

  { slug:'victor_hugo', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'France', birthplace:'Besançon', work:'Les Misérables', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Victor Hugo was a French writer, famous for enormous novels that mix adventure with a deep concern for justice. He was born in the city of Besançon in 1802 and became one of France's most celebrated authors and poets. Hugo cared deeply about the poor and the powerless, and he used his stories to expose the unfairness of society. His novel Les Misérables follows a man named Jean Valjean who is hunted for years after stealing a loaf of bread. Another famous book, The Hunchback of Notre-Dame, helped save the great Paris cathedral from being torn down. Hugo's powerful stories are still read and performed all over the world." },

  { slug:'mark_twain', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', work:'The Adventures of Tom Sawyer', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Mark Twain was an American writer known for his humor and his sharp eye for human nature. He was born Samuel Clemens in a small town in Missouri in 1835 and grew up along the Mississippi River. He took his pen name, Mark Twain, from a riverboat term, and he worked as a printer, a riverboat pilot, and a traveler before becoming a writer. His books The Adventures of Tom Sawyer and Adventures of Huckleberry Finn capture the adventures and troubles of boyhood in America. Twain used comedy to point out greed, dishonesty, and the cruelty of slavery. He is often called the father of American literature." },

  { slug:'fyodor_dostoevsky', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Russia', birthplace:'Moscow', work:'Crime and Punishment', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Fyodor Dostoevsky was a Russian writer famous for novels that dig deep into the human mind. He was born in Moscow in 1821 and led a hard life, once being arrested and nearly executed before his sentence was changed to prison in Siberia. These painful experiences gave him a powerful understanding of guilt, suffering, and hope. His novel Crime and Punishment follows a young man who commits a murder and is slowly crushed by his own conscience. Dostoevsky wrote about big questions of good and evil, faith and doubt. His stories are considered among the greatest and most psychological novels ever written." },

  { slug:'edgar_allan_poe', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Boston', work:'The Raven', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Edgar Allan Poe was an American writer known as a master of mystery and horror. He was born in Boston in 1809 and had a sad, troubled life marked by poverty and loss. Poe wrote spine-tingling short stories full of dread, madness, and the supernatural, such as 'The Tell-Tale Heart.' His famous poem 'The Raven,' with its haunting refrain 'Nevermore,' made him widely known. He is also credited with inventing the modern detective story. Though he struggled during his lifetime, Poe's chilling, imaginative tales have influenced writers and filmmakers ever since." },

  { slug:'mary_shelley', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'London', spouse:'Percy Bysshe Shelley', work:'Frankenstein', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Mary Shelley was an English writer who created one of the most famous stories of all time. She was born in London in 1797 to two well-known writers, and she loved books from an early age. As a teenager on a rainy holiday with friends, she took part in a contest to write a scary story. Her idea became the novel Frankenstein, about a scientist who builds a living creature and then abandons it. The book is often called the first work of science fiction, warning about the dangers of unchecked ambition. She was married to the poet Percy Bysshe Shelley, and her monster has haunted the imagination ever since." },

  { slug:'george_orwell', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', work:'1984', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"George Orwell was an English writer famous for warning about the dangers of dishonest and all-powerful governments. He was born in 1903, and his real name was Eric Blair. Orwell lived through poverty, war, and political struggle, which made him deeply distrustful of those who abuse power. In his novel Animal Farm, farm animals overthrow their farmer only to be ruled by cruel pigs, a clever fable about how revolutions can go wrong. His most famous book, 1984, imagines a future where the government watches and controls everyone's thoughts. Words he invented, like 'Big Brother,' are still used today to describe a loss of freedom." },

  { slug:'dmitri_mendeleev', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Russia', birthplace:'Tobolsk', work:'the periodic table', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Dmitri Mendeleev was a Russian chemist who brought order to the building blocks of matter. He was born in the town of Tobolsk in Siberia in 1834, the youngest of many children. Mendeleev studied the chemical elements — the basic substances that everything is made of — and searched for a pattern among them. In 1869 he arranged the elements into a chart now called the periodic table, grouping them by their properties. Amazingly, he left gaps for elements that had not yet been discovered and correctly predicted what they would be like. His periodic table hangs in science classrooms around the world and remains one of the great achievements of chemistry." },

  { slug:'antoine_lavoisier', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'France', birthplace:'Paris', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Antoine Lavoisier was a French scientist often called the father of modern chemistry. He was born in Paris in 1743 and used careful measurement to turn chemistry into an exact science. Lavoisier proved that matter is never created or destroyed in a chemical reaction, only rearranged — a rule called the conservation of mass. He identified and named important gases, including oxygen, and helped create the system for naming chemicals still used today. Sadly, during the French Revolution he was wrongly executed by guillotine. Yet his precise, careful methods changed chemistry forever." },

  { slug:'kublai_khan', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Mongolia', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Kublai Khan was a Mongol emperor and the grandson of the great conqueror Genghis Khan. He was born in 1215 and completed his family's conquest of China, becoming the first foreign ruler of the whole country. He founded the Yuan dynasty and built a magnificent capital in what is now Beijing. Under his rule, trade flourished along the Silk Road, and he welcomed travelers from far away, including the Italian explorer Marco Polo. Kublai Khan encouraged art, science, and different religions across his vast empire. He is remembered as a powerful ruler who connected the East and West." },

  { slug:'suleiman_the_magnificent', facts:{ field:'sultan', country:'Turkey', birthplace:'Trabzon', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Suleiman the Magnificent was the most powerful sultan of the Ottoman Empire. He was born in the city of Trabzon in 1494 and ruled for 46 years, leading the empire to its golden age. Under Suleiman, Ottoman armies expanded into Europe, the Middle East, and North Africa, making the empire one of the strongest in the world. He was also known as a fair lawmaker, and his people called him 'the Lawgiver.' Suleiman supported great art and architecture, including magnificent mosques still admired today. His long, brilliant reign shaped the history of both Europe and the Middle East." },

  { slug:'akbar', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'India', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Akbar was one of the greatest emperors of the Mughal Empire, which ruled much of India. He was born in 1542 and became emperor as a boy, growing into a wise and powerful leader. Akbar expanded his empire but is especially remembered for how he governed. In a time of religious conflict, he encouraged respect among people of different faiths and even removed a tax on non-Muslims. He welcomed artists, scholars, and thinkers of many religions to his court. Because of his fairness and love of learning, Akbar is honored as one of India's greatest rulers." },

  { slug:'ibn_sina', facts:{ field:'physician', country:'Persia', work:'The Canon of Medicine', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Ibn Sina, also known in the West as Avicenna, was a brilliant scholar of the Islamic Golden Age. He was born around 980 in Central Asia and was a child genius who mastered many subjects. Ibn Sina wrote about medicine, science, math, and philosophy, but he is most famous as a doctor. His giant book, The Canon of Medicine, collected and organized medical knowledge so well that it was used in schools for hundreds of years, even in Europe. He helped keep alive and expand the learning of the ancient world. Ibn Sina is remembered as one of the most important thinkers in the history of medicine." },

  { slug:'hammurabi', facts:{ field:'king', country:'Babylon', work:'his code of laws', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Hammurabi was a king of ancient Babylon, in what is now Iraq, who lived in the 1700s BCE. He united many cities under his rule and built one of the first great empires in the region of Mesopotamia. Hammurabi is most famous for creating one of the earliest written sets of laws in history. His code of laws was carved onto a tall stone pillar for everyone to see, so that people would know the rules. Many of the laws followed the idea of 'an eye for an eye,' matching the punishment to the crime. Hammurabi's code shows how ancient people tried to bring order and justice to their societies." },

  { slug:'hannibal', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Carthage', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Hannibal was a general from the ancient city of Carthage, in North Africa, and one of the greatest military commanders in history. He was born around 247 BCE, when Carthage and Rome were bitter enemies fighting for control of the Mediterranean. In a daring move, Hannibal led his army — including war elephants — over the snowy Alps to attack Rome from the north. He won several stunning victories against much larger Roman armies through clever strategy. In the end, Rome recovered and defeated Carthage, but Hannibal's bold tactics are still studied by soldiers today. He remains a legend of courage and military genius." },

  { slug:'pele', facts:{ field:'soccer player', country:'Brazil', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Pelé was a soccer player from Brazil, widely considered one of the greatest athletes of all time. He was born in 1940 and grew up so poor that he practiced with a sock stuffed with rags instead of a real ball. Pelé burst onto the world stage as a teenager, helping Brazil win the World Cup when he was just 17. Fast, skillful, and full of joy, he scored over a thousand goals in his career and won three World Cups. His talent helped make soccer the most popular sport on Earth. Known simply as 'the King,' Pelé became a global symbol of the beautiful game." },

  { slug:'jose_de_san_marti_n', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Argentina', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"José de San Martín was a general who helped free much of South America from Spanish rule. He was born in what is now Argentina in 1778 and trained as a soldier in Europe before returning to fight for his homeland's freedom. In one of history's boldest campaigns, San Martín led an army across the towering Andes Mountains to surprise the Spanish forces. His victories helped win independence for Argentina, Chile, and Peru. Unlike many leaders, he gave up power rather than fight for control after the wars. Together with Simón Bolívar, San Martín is honored as a great liberator of South America." },

  { slug:'alexander_hamilton', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', birthplace:'Nevis', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Alexander Hamilton was one of the Founding Fathers of the United States and its first Secretary of the Treasury. He was born on the Caribbean island of Nevis around 1755, poor and orphaned, but his brilliance won him a chance to study in America. Hamilton fought in the Revolutionary War and became a close aide to General George Washington. After independence, he designed the young country's banking and money system, helping it survive and grow. He also wrote many essays defending the new Constitution. Hamilton's life ended when he was killed in a duel, but his ideas still shape American finance and government." },

  { slug:'thomas_paine', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'Thetford', work:'Common Sense', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Thomas Paine was a writer whose words helped spark the American Revolution. He was born in the town of Thetford, England, in 1737 and moved to America just before the fight for independence began. In early 1776 he published a pamphlet called Common Sense, which argued in plain, powerful language that the colonies should break free from British rule. It sold hundreds of thousands of copies and convinced many ordinary people to support the revolution. Paine believed strongly in liberty and equal rights, and he later took part in the French Revolution too. His fiery writing showed how powerful ideas on paper can change history." },

  { slug:'patrick_henry', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Patrick Henry was an American leader famous for his fiery speeches during the fight for independence. He was born in the colony of Virginia in 1736 and became a skilled lawyer and public speaker. As tensions grew between the colonies and Britain, Henry urged Americans to resist unfair British rule. In one legendary speech, he is said to have cried, 'Give me liberty, or give me death!' — words that stirred the colonists to action. He later served as governor of Virginia and pushed for a Bill of Rights to protect people's freedoms. Patrick Henry is remembered as one of the boldest voices of the American Revolution." },

  { slug:'thurgood_marshall', facts:{ field:'lawyer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Baltimore', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Thurgood Marshall was a lawyer who became the first Black justice of the U.S. Supreme Court. He was born in Baltimore, Maryland, in 1908, at a time when segregation kept Black Americans apart in schools, buses, and stores. As a brilliant lawyer, Marshall fought unfair laws in court, winning case after case. His greatest victory came in 1954, when the Supreme Court agreed that segregated public schools were against the Constitution. In 1967 he was appointed to the Supreme Court himself, where he defended the rights of ordinary people. Thurgood Marshall changed America by proving that the law could be a powerful tool for justice." },

  { slug:'ida_b_wells', facts:{ field:'journalist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Holly Springs', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Ida B. Wells was a brave journalist who fought against racism and violence in the United States. She was born enslaved in Holly Springs, Mississippi, in 1862, just before slavery ended. As a young woman, Wells became a newspaper writer and reported the truth about lynchings — the terrible murders of Black people by mobs. Her fearless reporting made her enemies, and her newspaper office was even destroyed, but she refused to be silenced. She also helped fight for women's right to vote. Ida B. Wells showed that careful, honest journalism could shine a light on injustice and demand change." },

  { slug:'booker_t_washington', facts:{ field:'educator', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Booker T. Washington was an educator who became one of the most influential Black leaders in America. He was born enslaved in Virginia around 1856 and, after freedom came, worked hard to get an education. In 1881 he founded the Tuskegee Institute, a school that trained Black students in useful trades and skills. Washington believed that education and steady economic progress could help Black Americans build better lives. His approach was sometimes criticized by leaders who wanted to demand equal rights more forcefully. Still, Booker T. Washington helped thousands of students and showed the power of education to change lives." },

  { slug:'w_e_b_du_bois', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Great Barrington', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"W. E. B. Du Bois was a writer, scholar, and civil rights leader in the United States. He was born in Great Barrington, Massachusetts, in 1868 and became the first Black person to earn a doctorate from Harvard University. In his book The Souls of Black Folk, Du Bois described the pain and strength of Black life in America. Unlike some leaders of his time, he insisted that Black Americans should demand full equal rights right away. He helped found the NAACP, an organization that still fights for civil rights today. Du Bois spent his long life using his sharp mind and pen to challenge racism." },

  { slug:'malcolm_x', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Omaha', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Malcolm X was a powerful and controversial leader during the American civil rights era. He was born Malcolm Little in Omaha, Nebraska, in 1925 and faced racism, poverty, and hardship growing up. In prison as a young man, he educated himself and became a passionate speaker for Black pride and self-defense. Unlike Martin Luther King Jr., Malcolm X at first argued that Black Americans should not rely on peaceful protest alone. Later in life, after a journey to Mecca, he began to hope for unity among people of all races. Though he was assassinated in 1965, his call for dignity and self-respect still inspires people today." },

  { slug:'cesar_chavez', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Yuma', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Cesar Chavez was a labor leader who fought for the rights of farmworkers in the United States. He was born near Yuma, Arizona, in 1927, and as a boy his family lost their farm and became migrant workers, picking crops for very low pay. Chavez saw how badly these workers were treated and decided to organize them. He co-founded a union and led peaceful strikes, marches, and boycotts to demand fair wages and safe conditions. His rallying cry, 'Sí, se puede' — 'Yes, it can be done' — gave people hope. Through nonviolent action, Cesar Chavez won real improvements and became a hero to working people." },

  { slug:'george_washington_carver', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"George Washington Carver was an American scientist who helped transform farming in the South. He was born enslaved in Missouri around 1864, near the end of the Civil War, and had to fight hard just to get an education. Carver became an expert in plants and soil at the Tuskegee Institute. He taught poor farmers to protect their soil by growing crops like peanuts and sweet potatoes instead of only cotton. Then he invented hundreds of useful products from those crops so farmers could sell them. Carver's clever science and generosity improved the lives of countless struggling farmers." },

  { slug:'sally_ride', facts:{ field:'astronaut', country:'United States', birthplace:'Los Angeles', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Sally Ride was an astronaut who became the first American woman to travel into space. She was born in Los Angeles, California, in 1951 and grew up loving both sports and science, earning a doctorate in physics. In 1983 she flew aboard the space shuttle Challenger, breaking a barrier that had kept American women out of space. Ride helped operate the shuttle's robotic arm and carried out science experiments in orbit. After her flights, she devoted herself to encouraging girls to study science, math, and engineering. Sally Ride proved that space belongs to everyone, no matter their gender." },

  { slug:'duke_ellington', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Washington', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Duke Ellington was an American composer and bandleader and one of the giants of jazz. He was born in Washington, D.C., in 1899 and earned the nickname 'Duke' for his elegant style. Leading his own orchestra for decades, Ellington wrote and performed thousands of pieces, from toe-tapping dance tunes to grand concert works. He treated jazz as serious art and showcased the special talents of each musician in his band. Songs like 'It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)' became classics. Duke Ellington helped make jazz respected around the world as one of America's greatest gifts to music." },

  { slug:'elizabeth_i', facts:{ field:'queen', country:'England', birthplace:'Greenwich', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Elizabeth I was one of the most famous and successful queens in the history of England. She was born in Greenwich in 1533, the daughter of King Henry VIII. Elizabeth became queen during a dangerous time of religious conflict and threats from foreign powers. She ruled with intelligence and strength, and under her leadership England grew stronger and more united. In 1588 her navy defeated the mighty Spanish Armada, a huge fleet sent to invade. Her long reign, called the Elizabethan era, was a golden age of exploration and of writers like William Shakespeare. Elizabeth never married and is remembered as one of England's greatest rulers." },

  { slug:'louis_xiv', facts:{ field:'king', country:'France', work:'the Palace of Versailles', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Louis XIV was the powerful king of France known as the 'Sun King.' He was born in 1638 and became king as a young boy, going on to rule for an astonishing 72 years — the longest of any European monarch. Louis believed a king should have complete power, and he controlled France more tightly than any ruler before him. He built the enormous and glittering Palace of Versailles, where he kept the nobles close and under his eye. Under Louis, France led Europe in art, fashion, and culture, but his many costly wars left the country deep in debt. His grand, absolute rule became a model — and a warning — for kings across Europe." },

  { slug:'augustus', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Rome', birthplace:'Rome', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Augustus was the first emperor of ancient Rome and the founder of the Roman Empire. He was born in Rome in 63 BCE and was the grand-nephew and heir of Julius Caesar. After Caesar was assassinated, Augustus fought and outmaneuvered his rivals to gain control of Rome. Rather than call himself a king, he cleverly kept the appearance of the old republic while holding real power himself. Under Augustus, Rome enjoyed a long period of peace and prosperity known as the Pax Romana, or 'Roman Peace.' He rebuilt the city in marble and shaped an empire that would last for centuries." },

  { slug:'ernest_hemingway', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Oak Park', work:'The Old Man and the Sea', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Ernest Hemingway was an American writer famous for his short, powerful sentences and adventurous life. He was born in Oak Park, Illinois, in 1899 and worked as a newspaper reporter before becoming a novelist. Hemingway drove an ambulance in World War I and reported from wars and safaris, using his real experiences in his fiction. He wrote in a plain, direct style that stripped away extra words and influenced countless writers. His short novel The Old Man and the Sea tells of an old fisherman's epic struggle with a giant fish. Hemingway won the Nobel Prize in Literature and remains one of the most admired American authors." },

  { slug:'oscar_wilde', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Ireland', birthplace:'Dublin', work:'The Importance of Being Earnest', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Oscar Wilde was an Irish writer famous for his wit, humor, and sparkling conversation. He was born in Dublin in 1854 and became a celebrity in London for his clever sayings and colorful style. Wilde wrote poems, essays, and one novel, but he is best loved for his comic plays. His play The Importance of Being Earnest pokes fun at the silly manners of high society. He filled his work with clever one-liners that people still quote today. Though his life ended in scandal and hardship, Oscar Wilde is remembered as one of the funniest and most quotable writers in the English language." },

  { slug:'emily_dickinson', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'United States', birthplace:'Amherst', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Emily Dickinson was an American poet whose short, surprising poems are now considered some of the greatest ever written. She was born in Amherst, Massachusetts, in 1830 and lived a quiet, private life, rarely leaving her family's home. Dickinson wrote nearly 1,800 poems, often about nature, death, love, and the mysteries of the soul. Her poems used unusual dashes and slant rhymes that made them feel fresh and modern. Almost none of them were published while she was alive, and her genius was discovered only after she died. Today Emily Dickinson is celebrated as one of America's most original and beloved poets." },

  { slug:'j_r_r_tolkien', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', work:'The Lord of the Rings', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"J. R. R. Tolkien was an English writer who created some of the most beloved fantasy stories of all time. He was born in 1892 and became a professor who studied ancient languages and old myths. Tolkien loved language so much that he invented entire imaginary languages, and then built whole worlds to go with them. His books The Hobbit and The Lord of the Rings take place in a richly detailed land called Middle-earth, filled with hobbits, elves, and dragons. These stories about courage, friendship, and the fight against evil have sold hundreds of millions of copies. Tolkien is often called the father of modern fantasy." },

  { slug:'dante_alighieri', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Florence', work:'the Divine Comedy', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Dante Alighieri was an Italian poet from the Middle Ages, considered one of the greatest writers who ever lived. He was born in the city of Florence around 1265 and became involved in the fierce politics of his time, which got him exiled from his beloved city. In exile, Dante wrote a long poem called the Divine Comedy, which imagines a journey through the afterlife. The poem describes visits to the punishments of the underworld, the mountain of purification, and the glory of paradise. Dante wrote in the everyday Italian language of his region instead of Latin, which helped shape the Italian language itself. His masterpiece has inspired artists and readers for over 700 years." },

  { slug:'salvador_dali', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Spain', birthplace:'Figueres', work:'Surrealism', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Salvador Dalí was a Spanish painter famous for his strange, dreamlike art. He was born in the town of Figueres in 1904 and showed extraordinary painting skill from a young age. Dalí became a leader of a movement called Surrealism, which tried to paint the wild, illogical images of dreams and the imagination. His most famous painting shows soft, melting clocks draped across a bare landscape. With his curled mustache and outrageous behavior, Dalí turned himself into a walking work of art. His bizarre, unforgettable images made Surrealism one of the most recognizable styles in modern art." },

  { slug:'andy_warhol', facts:{ field:'artist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Pittsburgh', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Andy Warhol was an American artist who became the most famous figure in a movement called Pop Art. He was born in Pittsburgh in 1928 and worked as an advertising illustrator before becoming a fine artist. Warhol turned everyday objects and famous faces into art, creating bright, repeated images of soup cans and movie stars. He believed that art and popular culture — advertising, celebrities, shopping — belonged together. Working in a studio he called 'the Factory,' he also made films and helped launch new music. Warhol changed how people think about art, fame, and the images all around us in modern life." },

  { slug:'niels_bohr', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Denmark', birthplace:'Copenhagen', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Niels Bohr was a scientist from Denmark who helped unlock the secrets of the atom. He was born in Copenhagen in 1885 and became one of the leading physicists of his time. Bohr created a new picture of the atom, showing tiny electrons circling a central core, or nucleus. His work was a major step in the strange and powerful science of quantum physics. During World War II, Bohr fled the Nazis and helped other scientists, and afterward he urged the world to use atomic power peacefully. He won the Nobel Prize and trained many young scientists who went on to make discoveries of their own." },

  { slug:'alan_turing', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'England', birthplace:'London', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Alan Turing was a mathematician from England whose ideas helped create the modern computer. He was born in London in 1912 and showed a genius for math and logic from an early age. Turing imagined a machine that could follow instructions to solve any problem — a concept at the heart of every computer today. During World War II, he led a secret team that cracked the German military's coded messages, helping the Allies win the war and saving countless lives. After the war, he explored whether machines could one day 'think,' an idea we now call artificial intelligence. Turing was treated cruelly and unfairly for being gay, but today he is honored as a founder of computer science." },

  { slug:'alexander_graham_bell', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'Scotland', birthplace:'Edinburgh', work:'the telephone', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Alexander Graham Bell was an inventor best known for creating the telephone. He was born in Edinburgh, Scotland, in 1847 and later moved to North America. Bell's mother and wife were both deaf, and he spent much of his life studying sound, speech, and how to help deaf people communicate. This work led him to experiment with sending the human voice through wires. In 1876 he made the first telephone call, speaking to his assistant in another room. The telephone changed the world by letting people talk across great distances, and Bell went on to work on many other inventions throughout his life." },

  { slug:'florence_nightingale', facts:{ field:'nurse', country:'England', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Florence Nightingale was an English nurse who transformed the care of the sick. She was born in 1820 into a wealthy family who expected her to marry, but she felt called to help the suffering. During a war in the 1850s, Nightingale led a team of nurses to care for wounded British soldiers in filthy, crowded hospitals. By insisting on cleanliness, fresh air, and good food, she saved many lives, and soldiers called her 'the Lady with the Lamp' for checking on them at night. Afterward she used careful statistics to prove that clean hospitals saved lives, and she founded a famous nursing school. Florence Nightingale turned nursing into a respected, modern profession." },

  { slug:'ho_chi_minh', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'Vietnam', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Ho Chi Minh was a revolutionary leader who fought for the independence of Vietnam. He was born in 1890, at a time when Vietnam was ruled as a colony by France. As a young man he traveled the world, working many jobs and studying ideas about freedom and communism. Returning home, Ho Chi Minh led a long struggle to free his country, first from France and later during a war involving the United States. He became the leader of North Vietnam and a symbol of his people's fight for independence. Though he died before the war ended, Vietnam's largest city was later renamed Ho Chi Minh City in his honor." },

  { slug:'murasaki_shikibu', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Japan', work:'The Tale of Genji', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Murasaki Shikibu was a writer in ancient Japan who created what many consider the world's first novel. She was born around the year 978 and served as a lady-in-waiting in the royal court during Japan's elegant Heian period. Highly educated at a time when few women were taught to write, she recorded court life in her diary and poems. Her masterpiece, The Tale of Genji, tells the story of a charming prince and the people around him, exploring love, beauty, and sadness. Written a thousand years ago, it is still read and admired today. Murasaki Shikibu is celebrated as one of the greatest writers in Japanese history." },

  { slug:'enrico_fermi', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Rome', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Enrico Fermi was a physicist from Italy who helped launch the atomic age. He was born in Rome in 1901 and became one of the greatest scientists of his time, brilliant at both experiments and theory. As fascism rose in Italy, Fermi moved to the United States, where he studied the tiny particles inside atoms. In 1942 he led the team that built the first nuclear reactor, producing the first controlled release of nuclear energy. This breakthrough powered both nuclear weapons and peaceful electric plants. Fermi's careful genius earned him a place among the founders of modern physics." },

  { slug:'werner_heisenberg', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Würzburg', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Werner Heisenberg was a German physicist who helped create the strange science of quantum mechanics. He was born in the city of Würzburg in 1901 and became a leading thinker about the tiniest parts of nature. Heisenberg discovered his famous 'uncertainty principle,' which says that we can never know both the exact position and the exact speed of a tiny particle at the same time. This idea overturned old beliefs about how precisely the world can be measured. During World War II, he worked on Germany's nuclear program, a part of his life still debated by historians. Heisenberg's work reshaped how scientists understand reality at the smallest scale." },

  { slug:'erwin_schro_dinger', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Austria', birthplace:'Vienna', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Erwin Schrödinger was a physicist from Austria who helped build the theory of quantum mechanics. He was born in Vienna in 1887 and developed a famous equation that describes how tiny particles behave like waves. To show how odd the quantum world is, Schrödinger imagined a thought experiment about a cat in a box that is somehow both alive and dead until someone looks. This puzzle, known as 'Schrödinger's cat,' is still used to explain quantum ideas today. He won the Nobel Prize for his work and later fled the Nazis. Schrödinger showed that the rules of the very small are far stranger than everyday life." },

  { slug:'max_planck', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Kiel', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Max Planck was a German physicist who started one of the biggest revolutions in science. He was born in the city of Kiel in 1858 and studied how objects give off light and heat. In 1900, Planck made a startling discovery: energy is not smooth and continuous but comes in tiny, separate packets he called 'quanta.' This idea launched quantum physics, which explains the behavior of atoms and light. Planck's discovery changed science forever, even though it surprised him and other scientists. He is honored as the father of quantum theory, and a famous group of German research institutes is named after him." },

  { slug:'richard_feynman', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', birthplace:'New York City', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Richard Feynman was an American physicist famous for both his brilliance and his playful sense of fun. He was born in New York City in 1918 and loved solving puzzles of every kind. As a young man he helped build the first atomic bomb, and later he made deep discoveries about how light and matter interact, winning the Nobel Prize. Feynman was also a beloved teacher who could explain hard science in clear, exciting ways. He famously helped explain why a space shuttle exploded by dropping a rubber ring into ice water on live television. Feynman showed that great science could be curious, honest, and full of joy." },

  { slug:'robert_boyle', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Ireland', birthplace:'Lismore', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Robert Boyle was a scientist, born in Lismore, Ireland, in 1627, who helped turn chemistry into a real science. He lived at a time when many people still believed in alchemy — the magical idea of turning metals into gold. Boyle insisted that scientists should test their ideas with careful experiments instead of trusting old beliefs. He is famous for Boyle's law, which describes how the pressure of a gas changes as you squeeze it into a smaller space. He argued that everything is made of tiny particles, an early step toward the idea of atoms. Boyle helped create the modern scientific method that researchers still use today." },

  { slug:'james_watson', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Chicago', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"James Watson is an American scientist who helped discover the shape of DNA, the molecule of life. He was born in Chicago in 1928 and was a curious student who loved biology and birds. Working with the British scientist Francis Crick, Watson studied the chemical that carries the instructions for all living things. In 1953 they figured out that DNA is shaped like a twisted ladder, called a double helix. This discovery, which also relied on the crucial photographs taken by Rosalind Franklin, unlocked the secrets of how life passes traits from parents to children. Their work opened the door to modern genetics and biology." },

  { slug:'francis_crick', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'Northampton', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Francis Crick was an English scientist who, with James Watson, discovered the structure of DNA. He was born in Northampton in 1916 and worked on physics and radar during World War II before turning to biology. Crick was fascinated by the biggest question in life science: how do living things pass on their instructions? In 1953 he and Watson worked out that DNA is a double helix — a twisted, ladder-like shape — using key clues from Rosalind Franklin's research. This breakthrough explained how genes are copied and inherited. Crick spent the rest of his life exploring other deep mysteries, including how the brain creates consciousness." },

  { slug:'jonas_salk', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', birthplace:'New York City', work:'the polio vaccine', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Jonas Salk was an American scientist who developed one of the most important vaccines in history. He was born in New York City in 1914 and became a doctor determined to fight disease. In the early 1900s, a terrifying illness called polio paralyzed and killed thousands of children every year. Salk worked for years to create a vaccine that could protect people from polio, and in 1955 it was proven to work. He refused to patent the vaccine, choosing to let the whole world use it freely to save lives. Thanks to Jonas Salk, polio has nearly disappeared from the earth." },

  { slug:'alfred_nobel', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'Sweden', birthplace:'Stockholm', work:'dynamite', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Alfred Nobel was a Swedish inventor best remembered for the famous prizes that carry his name. He was born in Stockholm in 1833 and became a chemist and businessman. Nobel invented dynamite, a powerful explosive that made building tunnels, roads, and mines much easier — but that could also be used in war. Troubled that he might be remembered only for a tool of destruction, Nobel used his fortune to create a set of yearly prizes. The Nobel Prizes reward people who make great achievements in science, literature, and peace. Because of them, Alfred Nobel is now linked forever with human progress rather than with explosives." },

  { slug:'grace_hopper', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'United States', birthplace:'New York City', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Grace Hopper was an American mathematician and one of the great pioneers of computer science. She was born in New York City in 1906 and loved taking machines apart to see how they worked. During World War II she joined the Navy and helped program one of the first large computers. Hopper believed computers could be easier to use, so she helped create a way to give them instructions using words instead of just numbers. This idea led to programming languages that made computers useful for businesses and ordinary people. Known affectionately as 'Amazing Grace,' she helped shape the digital world we live in today." },

  { slug:'john_von_neumann', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Hungary', birthplace:'Budapest', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"John von Neumann was a Hungarian-American mathematician considered one of the smartest people of the 20th century. He was born in Budapest in 1903 and was a child prodigy who could do amazing calculations in his head. Von Neumann made important contributions to many fields, from pure math to physics to economics. Most famously, he helped design the basic plan that nearly all modern computers still follow, in which a computer stores both its data and its instructions in memory. He also worked on the atomic bomb and helped create game theory, a way of studying decisions. Few thinkers have influenced so many different areas of knowledge." },

  { slug:'j_robert_oppenheimer', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', birthplace:'New York City', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"J. Robert Oppenheimer was an American physicist known as the 'father of the atomic bomb.' He was born in New York City in 1904 and became a brilliant scientist and teacher. During World War II, the United States feared that Nazi Germany might build a super-weapon, so Oppenheimer was chosen to lead the secret Manhattan Project. His team of scientists succeeded in creating the first atomic bombs, which were used to end the war with terrible destruction. Deeply troubled by what he had helped unleash, Oppenheimer later argued against building even more powerful weapons. His life raises hard questions about science, war, and human responsibility." },

  { slug:'carl_sagan', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'United States', birthplace:'New York City', work:'Cosmos', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Carl Sagan was an American astronomer who helped millions of people fall in love with science. He was born in New York City in 1934 and grew up wondering about the stars. As a scientist, Sagan studied the planets and searched for signs of life beyond Earth. But he was best known as a communicator, especially through his television series Cosmos, which explored the universe with awe and wonder. He had a gift for explaining big ideas in simple, beautiful language, describing Earth as a 'pale blue dot' in the vastness of space. Carl Sagan taught people to feel both curiosity about the universe and care for our small planet." },

  { slug:'rachel_carson', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Springdale', work:'Silent Spring', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Rachel Carson was an American scientist and writer who helped start the modern environmental movement. She was born in Springdale, Pennsylvania, in 1907 and loved nature and writing from an early age. Carson studied biology and became an expert on the sea and its creatures. In her book Silent Spring, she warned that chemicals called pesticides were poisoning birds, fish, and even people. Her careful, powerful writing woke up the public and led to new laws protecting the environment. Rachel Carson showed how one determined scientist could change the way the whole world thinks about nature." },

  { slug:'lise_meitner', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Austria', birthplace:'Vienna', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Lise Meitner was a physicist from Austria who helped discover how to split the atom. She was born in Vienna in 1878, at a time when universities barely allowed women to study science. Meitner became a brilliant researcher, working for years alongside the chemist Otto Hahn. Together they studied what happens when atoms are struck by tiny particles. Meitner was the one who explained that the atom's center could split apart, releasing enormous energy — a process called nuclear fission. Forced to flee the Nazis because she was Jewish, she was unfairly left out when the Nobel Prize was given for the discovery. Today she is honored as one of the most important physicists of her time." },

  { slug:'emmy_noether', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Erlangen', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Emmy Noether was a German mathematician whose ideas are essential to modern math and physics. She was born in the town of Erlangen in 1882 and had to fight hard to study and teach, because universities of her time resisted women. Noether made deep discoveries in a branch of math called abstract algebra. She also proved a famous theorem showing a beautiful link between the symmetries of nature and the laws of physics, such as the conservation of energy. Great scientists, including Albert Einstein, praised her as a mathematical genius. Though many people have never heard of her, Emmy Noether's work quietly supports much of modern science." },

  { slug:'rosalind_franklin', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'London', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Rosalind Franklin was an English scientist whose work was crucial to discovering the structure of DNA. She was born in London in 1920 and became an expert at using X-rays to photograph tiny structures too small to see. Her careful, skillful photographs of DNA revealed important clues about its shape. Using her research, the scientists James Watson and Francis Crick worked out that DNA is a twisted double helix. For many years, Franklin's vital role was overlooked, and she died young, before the discovery won its Nobel Prize. Today Rosalind Franklin is celebrated as a brilliant scientist whose contribution helped unlock the secret of life." },

  { slug:'blaise_pascal', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'France', birthplace:'Clermont-Ferrand', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Blaise Pascal was a French mathematician, scientist, and thinker who was brilliant even as a child. He was born in the town of Clermont-Ferrand in 1623 and was doing advanced geometry while still a boy. To help his father with tax calculations, Pascal built one of the first mechanical calculating machines. He also helped create the mathematics of probability, which studies the chances of different outcomes. Later in life he turned to religion and philosophy, writing famous thoughts about faith and the human condition. A unit of pressure and a computer language are both named in his honor." },

  { slug:'george_frideric_handel', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Halle', work:'Messiah', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"George Frideric Handel was a composer, born in Halle, Germany, in 1685, who spent much of his career in England. He wrote operas, orchestral works, and grand pieces for choirs during the Baroque period of music. Handel's most famous work is Messiah, a magnificent piece for choir and orchestra whose 'Hallelujah' chorus is still sung around the world, especially at Christmas. He knew how to write music that felt both powerful and joyful, pleasing kings and ordinary audiences alike. Even after he went blind late in life, he kept performing. Handel remains one of the most beloved composers of his age." },

  { slug:'johannes_brahms', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Hamburg', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Johannes Brahms was a German composer and pianist ranked among the greatest musicians of the 1800s. He was born in the city of Hamburg in 1833 and grew up poor, playing piano in taverns to help his family. Brahms wrote rich, powerful symphonies, concertos, and chamber music that combined deep feeling with careful craftsmanship. He was admired for continuing the grand classical tradition of composers like Beethoven while adding his own warmth. One of his gentlest tunes, known simply as 'Brahms's Lullaby,' is still sung to babies everywhere. Brahms is remembered as a master who blended emotion with perfect musical form." },

  { slug:'igor_stravinsky', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Russia', work:'The Rite of Spring', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Igor Stravinsky was a Russian composer who shocked the world and changed modern music. He was born near St. Petersburg in 1882 and became famous for writing music for ballets. His most daring work, The Rite of Spring, had such wild rhythms and harsh sounds that its first performance in 1913 caused the audience to riot. Stravinsky was not afraid to break the old rules, constantly inventing new styles throughout his long career. His bold, rhythmic music influenced composers, filmmakers, and even rock musicians. Igor Stravinsky is remembered as one of the most original and influential composers of the 20th century." },

  { slug:'johannes_vermeer', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Netherlands', birthplace:'Delft', work:'Girl with a Pearl Earring', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Johannes Vermeer was a Dutch painter famous for his quiet, glowing scenes of everyday life. He was born in the town of Delft in 1632, during the golden age of Dutch art. Vermeer painted slowly and carefully, creating only a small number of works, mostly of people in calm indoor moments. He had an extraordinary gift for capturing soft, natural light falling across a room. His most famous painting, Girl with a Pearl Earring, shows a young woman gazing over her shoulder and is sometimes called the 'Mona Lisa of the North.' Almost forgotten for centuries, Vermeer is now treasured as one of the greatest painters who ever lived." },

  { slug:'titian', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Italy', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Titian was an Italian painter and one of the greatest artists of the Renaissance. He was born in a small town in northern Italy around 1488 and spent most of his long life working in the wealthy city of Venice. Titian was a master of color, using rich, glowing tones that made his paintings feel alive. He painted portraits of kings, popes, and emperors, as well as scenes from myth and religion. So respected was he that the powerful emperor Charles V is said to have picked up a paintbrush Titian dropped. His bold use of color influenced painters for centuries afterward." },

  { slug:'caravaggio', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Milan', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Caravaggio was an Italian painter who brought a shocking new drama to art. He was born near Milan in 1571 and lived a wild, violent life that often got him into trouble with the law. In his paintings, Caravaggio used harsh contrasts of bright light and deep shadow to make his figures leap out with startling realism. Instead of idealized saints, he painted ordinary, rough-looking people, which some found disturbing and others found powerful. His dramatic style, called chiaroscuro, influenced countless painters across Europe. Though his life was short and stormy, Caravaggio changed the course of Western painting." },

  { slug:'henri_matisse', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'France', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Henri Matisse was a French artist famous for his bold use of bright, joyful color. He was born in northern France in 1869 and only discovered painting as a young man, while recovering from an illness. Matisse became a leader of a group of artists who used such wild, vivid colors that critics called them 'wild beasts.' He believed that art should bring happiness and calm, like a comfortable chair after a hard day. Late in life, when he was too ill to paint at an easel, he created dazzling art by cutting shapes out of brightly colored paper. Matisse's cheerful, daring work made him one of the most important artists of modern times." },

  { slug:'sandro_botticelli', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Florence', work:'The Birth of Venus', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Sandro Botticelli was an Italian painter of the early Renaissance, famous for his graceful, flowing figures. He was born in the city of Florence around 1445 and worked for the powerful Medici family who ruled the city. Botticelli painted both religious scenes and stories from ancient Greek and Roman myths. His most famous painting, The Birth of Venus, shows the goddess of love rising from the sea on a giant shell. His delicate, dreamlike style made his art instantly recognizable. After centuries of being nearly forgotten, Botticelli is now seen as one of the treasures of the Italian Renaissance." },

  { slug:'auguste_rodin', facts:{ field:'sculptor', country:'France', birthplace:'Paris', work:'The Thinker', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Auguste Rodin was a French sculptor considered one of the greatest since the Renaissance. He was born in Paris in 1840 and was rejected from art school several times before finally winning fame. Rodin sculpted the human body in a strikingly lifelike and emotional way, capturing movement, struggle, and thought. His most famous statue, The Thinker, shows a powerful man sitting deep in thought, chin resting on his hand. At first some critics disliked his rough, unfinished-looking style, but audiences came to love its raw energy. Rodin helped free sculpture from strict old rules and is seen as the father of modern sculpture." },

  { slug:'gregor_mendel', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Austria', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Gregor Mendel was a scientist and monk who discovered the basic rules of how living things inherit traits. He was born in 1822 in what is now the Czech Republic and became a monk with a deep love of nature and math. In his monastery garden, Mendel spent years carefully breeding thousands of pea plants. By tracking traits like flower color and plant height, he figured out that parents pass hidden 'factors' to their offspring in predictable patterns. These factors are what we now call genes. Almost no one noticed his work during his life, but today Gregor Mendel is honored as the father of genetics." },

  { slug:'edwin_hubble', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Marshfield', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Edwin Hubble was an American astronomer who completely changed our view of the universe. He was born in Marshfield, Missouri, in 1889 and gave up a career in law to study the stars. Using one of the largest telescopes of his time, Hubble proved that our Milky Way is just one of countless galaxies scattered across space. He also discovered that these galaxies are rushing away from each other, which showed that the entire universe is expanding. This finding became a key piece of evidence that the universe began with a 'Big Bang.' The famous Hubble Space Telescope was named in his honor." },

  { slug:'guglielmo_marconi', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Bologna', work:'the radio', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Guglielmo Marconi was an Italian inventor who helped create wireless communication. He was born in the city of Bologna in 1874 and became fascinated with the idea of sending messages through the air without wires. Building on the work of earlier scientists, Marconi developed a system that could send radio signals across longer and longer distances. In 1901 he stunned the world by sending a wireless signal all the way across the Atlantic Ocean. His invention made it possible for ships at sea to call for help and for news to travel instantly. Marconi's radio was a giant step toward the connected, wireless world we live in today." },

  { slug:'wright_brothers', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'United States', work:'the first airplane', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"The Wright brothers, Orville and Wilbur, were American inventors who built the first successful airplane. They were born in the 1860s and 1870s and ran a bicycle shop in Ohio, where they learned to build light, strong machines. Fascinated by the dream of flight, they studied birds and tested wings in a homemade wind tunnel. In 1903, on a windy beach in North Carolina, their flying machine lifted off and stayed in the air for the first time. That flight lasted only twelve seconds, but it changed the world forever. Thanks to the Wright brothers, humans could finally fly." },

  { slug:'henry_ford', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'United States', birthplace:'Detroit', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Henry Ford was an American businessman who changed how the world builds and buys cars. He was born on a farm near Detroit in 1863 and was fascinated by machines from a young age. Ford did not invent the automobile, but he found a way to make cars cheap enough for ordinary families to afford. He built the moving assembly line, where each worker added one part as the car rolled past, letting factories produce cars quickly. His famous Model T put millions of people behind the wheel and reshaped cities and daily life. Ford's ideas about mass production spread to factories all over the world." },

  { slug:'charles_babbage', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'England', birthplace:'London', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Charles Babbage was an English mathematician often called the 'father of the computer.' He was born in London in 1791 and was frustrated by the many mistakes people made in doing calculations by hand. To solve this, Babbage designed remarkable machines made of gears and levers that could do math automatically. His most ambitious design, the Analytical Engine, contained many ideas found in modern computers, over a century before they were built. He worked closely with the mathematician Ada Lovelace, who wrote instructions for his machine. Though he never finished building it, Babbage imagined the computer age long before it arrived." },

  { slug:'tim_berners_lee', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'England', birthplace:'London', work:'the World Wide Web', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Tim Berners-Lee is an English computer scientist who invented the World Wide Web. He was born in London in 1955, the son of two computer pioneers. While working at a science laboratory in Europe, he wanted an easier way for scientists to share information stored on different computers. In 1989 he came up with the idea of the Web, creating the rules that let web pages link to one another. He wrote the first web browser and the first website, then gave his invention to the world for free. Because of Tim Berners-Lee, billions of people can now share knowledge across the internet with a single click." },

  { slug:'hippocrates', facts:{ field:'physician', country:'Greece', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Hippocrates was a physician in ancient Greece often called the father of medicine. He was born around 460 BCE on the island of Kos and lived at a time when many people believed illness was a punishment from the gods. Hippocrates taught instead that diseases have natural causes and can be studied and treated. He and his students kept careful notes on their patients and looked for patterns in how sicknesses developed. He believed doctors should always try to help and never harm their patients, an idea still central to medicine today. Many new doctors still promise to follow the values of the famous Hippocratic Oath, named after him." },

  { slug:'euclid', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Greece', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Euclid was a mathematician of the ancient world, often called the father of geometry. He lived around 300 BCE and worked in the great city of Alexandria, in Egypt, then a center of Greek learning. Euclid gathered together the mathematical knowledge of his time and organized it into a book called the Elements. In it, he built up geometry step by step, starting from a few simple, obvious rules and carefully proving everything else. His method of clear, logical proof became the model for how mathematics is done. The Elements was used as a textbook for more than two thousand years, longer than almost any other book." },

  { slug:'pythagoras', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Greece', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Pythagoras was an ancient Greek philosopher and mathematician whose name is still known to every geometry student. He was born on the island of Samos around 570 BCE and later started a community of followers who studied numbers, music, and the stars. Pythagoras believed that numbers held the secrets of the universe. He is famous for the Pythagorean theorem, a rule about right triangles that shows how the lengths of their sides are related. His followers even discovered that musical notes follow simple number patterns. Pythagoras helped begin the idea that math can describe the hidden order of the world." },

  { slug:'vasco_da_gama', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Portugal', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Vasco da Gama was a Portuguese explorer who found a sea route from Europe to India. He was born in Portugal around 1460, during an age when European nations were eager to reach the rich spice markets of Asia. In 1497 da Gama set sail south around the whole coast of Africa, a dangerous voyage no European had completed before. After many months, he reached India, opening a trade route that made Portugal wealthy and powerful. His journey connected Europe and Asia by sea for the first time. But the arrival of European ships also began centuries of conflict and colonial control in the region." },

  { slug:'ernest_shackleton', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'England', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Ernest Shackleton was a British explorer famous for one of history's greatest survival stories. He was born in 1874 and became determined to explore the frozen continent of Antarctica. In 1914 he set out to cross Antarctica on foot, but his ship, the Endurance, became trapped and was slowly crushed by the ice. Stranded far from help, Shackleton kept his crew alive through months of freezing hardship. He then led a small team on a daring open-boat journey across stormy seas to fetch rescue. Amazingly, every single member of his crew survived. Shackleton is remembered as a hero of leadership, courage, and never giving up." },

  { slug:'roald_amundsen', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Norway', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Roald Amundsen was a Norwegian explorer who was the first to reach the South Pole. He was born in 1872 and dreamed of polar adventure from the time he was a boy. Amundsen prepared for his expeditions with extreme care, learning survival skills from the Inuit people of the Arctic. In 1911 he led a small team racing across the Antarctic ice, reaching the South Pole ahead of a British group led by Robert Scott. His success came from careful planning, good equipment, and skilled use of sled dogs. Amundsen also explored the Arctic, becoming one of the greatest polar explorers who ever lived." },

  { slug:'yuri_gagarin', facts:{ field:'astronaut', country:'Russia', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Yuri Gagarin was a Soviet pilot who became the first human being to travel into space. He was born in a small village in Russia in 1934 and grew up loving airplanes, eventually becoming a fighter pilot. During the Cold War, the Soviet Union and the United States were racing to explore space. In 1961 Gagarin climbed into a small spacecraft called Vostok 1 and orbited the entire Earth in about 108 minutes. His flight was a stunning achievement that thrilled and amazed the whole world. Yuri Gagarin became an international hero and proved that humans could survive and travel beyond our planet." },

  { slug:'peter_the_great', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Russia', birthplace:'Moscow', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Peter the Great was a Russian ruler who dragged his country into the modern age. He was born in Moscow in 1672 and grew into an enormously tall, energetic, and curious man. Peter traveled in disguise to western Europe to learn about shipbuilding, science, and government, then brought these new ideas back to Russia. He built a powerful navy, reformed the army, and forced the nobles to adopt European styles, even taxing long beards. He also built a brand-new capital city, St. Petersburg, on land won from his enemies. Through harsh but determined rule, Peter the Great turned Russia into a major European power." },

  { slug:'otto_von_bismarck', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'Germany', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Otto von Bismarck was a German statesman who united many separate states into a single country of Germany. He was born in 1815 into a noble family and became a powerful and cunning politician. At the time, the German-speaking lands were divided into dozens of kingdoms and duchies. Through clever diplomacy and a series of carefully chosen wars, Bismarck brought them together under the leadership of Prussia in 1871. Known as the 'Iron Chancellor,' he was famous for the ruthless idea that great questions are settled by 'blood and iron.' The powerful, unified Germany that Bismarck created reshaped the balance of power in Europe." },

  { slug:'pericles', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Athens', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Pericles was a leader of the ancient Greek city of Athens during its greatest age. He was born in Athens around 495 BCE and became the city's most influential statesman. Pericles strengthened Athenian democracy, giving ordinary citizens more power to take part in government than almost anywhere else in the ancient world. He also used the city's wealth to fund magnificent buildings, including the famous Parthenon temple that still stands today. Under his leadership, Athens became a center of art, philosophy, and learning. This brilliant period is often called the 'Age of Pericles' in his honor." },

  { slug:'constantine_the_great', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Rome', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Constantine the Great was a Roman emperor who changed the course of history and religion. He was born around 272 CE and fought his way to become the sole ruler of the vast Roman Empire. Constantine is most famous for becoming the first Roman emperor to support Christianity, which had long been a persecuted religion. He made it legal to be a Christian and helped the faith grow into one of the world's major religions. He also built a grand new capital city called Constantinople, at the crossroads of Europe and Asia. Constantine's decisions shaped both the Roman world and the future of Christianity." },

  { slug:'darius_the_great', facts:{ field:'king', country:'Persia', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Darius the Great was a king who ruled the enormous Persian Empire at the height of its power. He was born around 550 BCE and took control of an empire that stretched across much of the ancient Middle East. Darius was a gifted organizer who divided his lands into provinces, each governed by an official who answered to him. He built a network of roads, including a 'Royal Road' that let messengers travel across the empire quickly. He also created a fair system of taxes and coins to help trade. Though his armies were later defeated by the Greeks, Darius is remembered as one of the greatest rulers of the ancient world." },

  { slug:'xerxes_i', facts:{ field:'king', country:'Persia', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Xerxes I was a king of the mighty Persian Empire, famous for his massive invasion of Greece. He was the son of Darius the Great and became king around 486 BCE. Determined to conquer the Greeks who had defeated his father, Xerxes gathered one of the largest armies the ancient world had ever seen. At a narrow mountain pass called Thermopylae, a small band of Greek soldiers, including 300 Spartans, held off his huge army for days. Although Xerxes captured and burned Athens, the Greeks eventually defeated his navy and forced him to retreat. His failed invasion became one of the most famous stories of the ancient world." },

  { slug:'johann_wolfgang_von_goethe', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Frankfurt', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Johann Wolfgang von Goethe was a German writer often considered the greatest in the German language. He was born in the city of Frankfurt in 1749 and showed astonishing talent in many fields. Goethe wrote poems, plays, and novels, and he was also a scientist, a government official, and a thinker. As a young man, his emotional novel The Sorrows of Young Werther made him famous across Europe. His masterpiece is a long play called Faust, about a scholar who makes a bargain with the devil for knowledge and experience. Goethe's enormous range of talents made him a towering figure of world literature." },

  { slug:'hans_christian_andersen', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Denmark', birthplace:'Odense', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Hans Christian Andersen was a Danish writer who created some of the most beloved fairy tales in the world. He was born in the town of Odense in 1805, the son of a poor shoemaker, and dreamed of becoming famous. As an adult, Andersen wrote fairy tales that were more than just simple children's stories — they carried deep feelings and lessons about life. His tales include 'The Little Mermaid,' 'The Ugly Duckling,' and 'The Emperor's New Clothes.' Many of his stories reflected his own experiences of feeling different and longing to be accepted. Today his fairy tales are translated into more languages than almost any other book, delighting readers of every age." },

  { slug:'lewis_carroll', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', work:'Alice in Wonderland', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Lewis Carroll was an English writer famous for creating one of the most imaginative stories ever written. He was born in 1832, and his real name was Charles Dodgson. In his everyday life he was a shy mathematics teacher at Oxford University who loved puzzles and wordplay. One day, while entertaining some children on a boat trip, he made up a tale about a girl who falls down a rabbit hole. That story became the book Alice's Adventures in Wonderland, filled with talking animals, riddles, and delightful nonsense. Its playful language and dreamlike logic have enchanted readers for over 150 years." },

  { slug:'antonio_vivaldi', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Venice', work:'The Four Seasons', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Antonio Vivaldi was an Italian composer whose lively music is still hugely popular today. He was born in the city of Venice in 1678 and became a Catholic priest, earning the nickname 'the Red Priest' for his red hair. Vivaldi worked at a school for orphaned girls, where he trained a famous orchestra and wrote music for them to perform. He composed hundreds of concertos, pieces that let a solo instrument shine against a full orchestra. His most beloved work, The Four Seasons, uses music to paint pictures of spring, summer, autumn, and winter. Vivaldi's energetic, colorful music helped shape the whole Baroque style." },

  { slug:'richard_wagner', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Leipzig', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Richard Wagner was a German composer known for his enormous and dramatic operas. He was born in the city of Leipzig in 1813 and set out to change what opera could be. Wagner wrote both the music and the words for his works and combined singing, orchestra, story, and stage design into one grand experience. His most ambitious project, a cycle of four connected operas called the Ring, tells an epic tale of gods, heroes, and a magic ring, and takes many hours to perform. His powerful, sweeping music influenced later composers and even film scores. Wagner was also a deeply controversial figure whose harmful prejudices are still debated today." },

  { slug:'georgia_o_keeffe', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Georgia O'Keeffe was an American painter often called the 'mother of American modernism.' She was born in Wisconsin in 1887 and knew from a young age that she wanted to be an artist. O'Keeffe became famous for her large, close-up paintings of flowers, which she painted so big that viewers could see them in a whole new way. She also fell in love with the deserts of New Mexico and painted its bones, hills, and wide skies in bold, simple shapes. Her unique style did not copy anyone else, and she kept creating art into her nineties. Georgia O'Keeffe helped shape modern American art with her clear, powerful vision." },

  { slug:'james_madison', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', spouse:'Dolley Madison', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"James Madison was the fourth president of the United States and is often called the 'Father of the Constitution.' He was born in Virginia in 1751 and, though small and soft-spoken, had one of the sharpest minds among the country's founders. At the convention that wrote the Constitution, Madison took detailed notes and shaped many of its key ideas about how to balance power in government. He also helped write the Bill of Rights, which protects freedoms like speech and religion. As president, he led the country through the War of 1812 against Britain. He was married to Dolley Madison, a famous and beloved first lady." },

  { slug:'barack_obama', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Honolulu', spouse:'Michelle Obama', era:'in the 2000s' },
    text:"Barack Obama was the 44th president of the United States and the first Black person to hold the office. He was born in Honolulu, Hawaii, in 1961, the son of a father from Kenya and a mother from Kansas. Obama worked as a community organizer and a lawyer before entering politics and rising quickly to national fame. In 2008 he was elected president, a historic milestone in a country that had once allowed slavery and segregation. As president, he passed a major health-care law and guided the country through a serious economic crisis. He was married to Michelle Obama, and his election gave hope to many people around the world." },

  { slug:'james_clerk_maxwell', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Scotland', birthplace:'Edinburgh', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"James Clerk Maxwell was a scientist from Scotland whose work is often ranked with that of Newton and Einstein. He was born in Edinburgh in 1831 and showed a genius for science and math while very young. Maxwell studied electricity and magnetism and made an astonishing discovery: that they are two sides of the same force, which he called electromagnetism. He wrote a small set of equations that describe how this force works, and from them he realized that light itself is an electromagnetic wave. His ideas made possible radio, television, and countless modern technologies. Maxwell is remembered as one of the most important physicists in history." },

  { slug:'leonhard_euler', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Switzerland', birthplace:'Basel', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Leonhard Euler was a Swiss mathematician considered one of the greatest who ever lived. He was born in the city of Basel in 1707 and made discoveries in nearly every area of math. Euler introduced many of the symbols and ideas that students still use today, and he solved problems that had stumped others for years. He was so productive that he kept writing brilliant math even after he became completely blind, doing the calculations in his head. He also helped create new fields, such as the study of networks and shapes. Euler's countless contributions form a foundation of modern mathematics." },

  { slug:'carl_friedrich_gauss', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Brunswick', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Carl Friedrich Gauss was a German mathematician sometimes called the 'Prince of Mathematicians.' He was born in the city of Brunswick in 1777 into a poor family, but his genius appeared early. A famous story says that as a young schoolboy he instantly added all the numbers from 1 to 100 by spotting a clever pattern. Gauss made major discoveries in number theory, geometry, and the study of statistics. He also used math to predict the path of a newly discovered space rock, astonishing astronomers. His work touched almost every branch of mathematics and science." },

  { slug:'rudolf_diesel', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Paris', work:'the diesel engine', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Rudolf Diesel was a German inventor who created a powerful new kind of engine. He was born in Paris in 1858 to German parents and studied to become an engineer. Diesel wanted to build an engine that was more efficient and used less fuel than the steam engines of his day. After years of work, he invented the engine that now bears his name, which ignites fuel using heat from high pressure instead of a spark. The diesel engine became a workhorse for trucks, ships, trains, and heavy machines around the world. Though Diesel's own life ended mysteriously, his invention still powers much of modern transportation." },

  { slug:'franz_schubert', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Austria', birthplace:'Vienna', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Franz Schubert was an Austrian composer famous for his beautiful and emotional music. He was born near Vienna in 1797 and showed extraordinary musical talent as a child. In his short life, Schubert composed an astonishing amount of music, including symphonies, piano pieces, and hundreds of songs. He was a master of the art song, setting poems to music that captured deep feelings in just a few minutes. Some of his greatest works were not even performed until after he died at only 31. Today Franz Schubert is loved as one of the most gifted melody-writers in the history of music." },

  { slug:'ella_fitzgerald', facts:{ field:'singer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Newport News', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Ella Fitzgerald was an American singer known as the 'First Lady of Song' for her flawless jazz voice. She was born in Newport News, Virginia, in 1917 and had a hard childhood, sometimes living on the streets. Her big break came when she nervously stepped on stage at a talent show and amazed the audience with her singing. Ella became famous for her clear tone, perfect pitch, and her playful 'scat' singing, in which she used her voice like an instrument. She recorded beloved songs by America's greatest composers and won many awards. Ella Fitzgerald is remembered as one of the greatest jazz singers of all time." },

  { slug:'virgil', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'Rome', work:'the Aeneid', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Virgil was a poet of ancient Rome, considered its greatest. He was born around 70 BCE, near the northern Italian city of Mantua, and lived during the age of the first Roman emperor, Augustus. Virgil wrote poems about farming and the countryside before beginning his masterpiece, the Aeneid. This long epic poem tells the story of the hero Aeneas, who escapes the fall of the city of Troy and journeys to Italy to found the ancestors of the Roman people. The poem gave Rome a grand founding legend and became one of the most important works in Western literature. For centuries, Virgil was treated as the model of the perfect poet." },

  { slug:'geoffrey_chaucer', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'England', birthplace:'London', work:'The Canterbury Tales', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Geoffrey Chaucer was an English poet often called the father of English literature. He was born in London around 1343 and worked many jobs, including soldier, government official, and diplomat. In Chaucer's time, important writing was usually done in Latin or French, but he chose to write in the everyday English of ordinary people. His masterpiece, The Canterbury Tales, tells the funny and lively stories of a group of travelers on a religious journey. The characters — from a knight to a miller to a cook — feel real and human even today. By writing in English, Chaucer helped make it a respected language for great literature." },

  { slug:'agatha_christie', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'Torquay', work:'Murder on the Orient Express', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Agatha Christie was an English writer and the best-selling novelist of all time. She was born in the seaside town of Torquay in 1890 and began writing mystery stories to entertain herself. Christie became the queen of the detective novel, inventing clever crimes and even cleverer detectives to solve them. Her most famous characters are the brilliant Belgian detective Hercule Poirot and the sharp-eyed Miss Marple. Books like Murder on the Orient Express keep readers guessing until the very last page. Agatha Christie's mysteries have sold billions of copies and are still loved by readers around the world." },

  { slug:'walt_whitman', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'United States', work:'Leaves of Grass', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Walt Whitman was an American poet often called the father of free verse. He was born on New York's Long Island in 1819 and worked as a printer, teacher, and newspaper writer. Whitman broke away from the strict rhymes and rhythms of traditional poetry, writing in long, flowing lines that sounded like natural speech. His great collection of poems, Leaves of Grass, celebrated ordinary people, nature, democracy, and the human body. During the Civil War, he cared for wounded soldiers, an experience that deepened his poetry. Walt Whitman's bold, joyful voice helped shape a distinctly American kind of literature." },

  { slug:'susan_b_anthony', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Adams', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Susan B. Anthony was an American activist who dedicated her life to winning women the right to vote. She was born in Adams, Massachusetts, in 1820 into a family that believed in equality and justice. Anthony organized meetings, gave speeches, and gathered signatures to demand voting rights for women. In 1872 she was even arrested for voting, which was against the law for women at the time. Though she did not live to see it, her tireless work helped lead to the 19th Amendment in 1920, which finally gave American women the vote. Susan B. Anthony's determination made her one of the most important leaders in the fight for equal rights." },

  { slug:'sojourner_truth', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Sojourner Truth was an American activist who fought against slavery and for women's rights. She was born enslaved in New York around 1797 and was sold away from her family as a child. After she gained her freedom, she chose the new name Sojourner Truth to reflect her mission to travel and speak the truth. Though she could not read or write, she became a powerful public speaker. In a famous speech, she is remembered for demanding that Black women be treated as equals. Sojourner Truth's courage and honesty made her one of the most memorable voices in the fight for freedom and equality." },

  { slug:'charles_lindbergh', facts:{ field:'aviator', country:'United States', birthplace:'Detroit', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Charles Lindbergh was an American pilot who became world-famous for a daring flight across the Atlantic Ocean. He was born in Detroit in 1902 and fell in love with flying as a young man. In 1927, Lindbergh flew alone from New York to Paris in a small plane called the Spirit of St. Louis. The journey took more than 33 hours, during which he fought exhaustion and had no radio or copilot. When he landed, he was greeted as an international hero, and his flight showed that long-distance air travel was possible. Lindbergh's courage helped inspire the rapid growth of aviation." },

  { slug:'amerigo_vespucci', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Florence', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Amerigo Vespucci was an Italian explorer and mapmaker whose name lives on in two whole continents. He was born in the city of Florence around 1454 and sailed on voyages across the Atlantic Ocean to the New World. Unlike Christopher Columbus, who believed he had reached Asia, Vespucci argued that the lands were an entirely new, unknown continent. His writings about these 'new worlds' became widely read across Europe. A mapmaker was so impressed that he labeled the new lands 'America,' after Amerigo's first name. Because of this, the continents of North and South America carry his name to this day." },

  { slug:'john_locke', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'England', birthplace:'Wrington', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"John Locke was an English philosopher whose ideas helped shape modern democracy. He was born in the village of Wrington in 1632, during a time of great conflict between kings and Parliament in England. Locke argued that all people are born with natural rights to life, liberty, and property. He believed that governments exist only to protect these rights, and that a ruler who abuses power can rightly be replaced. He also thought the human mind begins like a blank slate, filled in by experience. Locke's ideas about rights and government deeply influenced the American Declaration of Independence and revolutions around the world." },

  { slug:'cai_lun', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'China', work:'paper', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Cai Lun was an official in ancient China who is honored for improving one of history's most important inventions: paper. He lived around the year 100 CE and served in the court of the Chinese emperor. Before his time, people wrote on heavy bamboo strips or expensive silk, which were awkward and costly. Cai Lun developed a much better way to make paper by mashing together materials like tree bark, rags, and old fishing nets. His cheap, light, and smooth paper made writing and record-keeping far easier. Over the centuries, papermaking spread across the world, changing the way people share knowledge forever." },

  { slug:'tokugawa_ieyasu', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Japan', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Tokugawa Ieyasu was a Japanese warlord who ended centuries of war and united Japan under his rule. He was born in 1543, during a violent age when powerful lords fought one another for control. A patient and clever leader, Ieyasu won a decisive battle in the year 1600 that made him the most powerful man in Japan. He became shogun, the top military ruler, and founded a family dynasty that would govern Japan for over 250 years. Under the Tokugawa, Japan enjoyed a long era of peace, order, and growing culture, largely closed off from the outside world. Ieyasu is remembered as one of the great unifiers of Japan." },

  { slug:'oda_nobunaga', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Japan', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Oda Nobunaga was a powerful and ruthless warlord who began the process of uniting Japan. He was born in 1534, at a time when Japan was torn apart by constant warfare among rival lords. Nobunaga was a bold and forward-thinking leader who was among the first in Japan to make heavy use of guns in battle. Through fierce campaigns, he conquered much of central Japan and broke the power of his enemies. Before he could finish uniting the country, he was betrayed and killed by one of his own generals. Still, Oda Nobunaga's conquests paved the way for others to bring lasting unity to Japan." },

  { slug:'emperor_meiji', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Japan', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Emperor Meiji was the Japanese ruler who led his country into the modern world. He was born in 1852 and became emperor as a teenager, at a moment when Japan had been closed off from the West for centuries. During his reign, Japan made an astonishing transformation known as the Meiji Restoration. The country built railroads, factories, schools, and a modern army and navy, quickly catching up with Western nations. Japan changed from an old feudal society into one of the most powerful industrial nations in the world. Emperor Meiji became a symbol of this dramatic leap into the modern age." },

  { slug:'sun_yat_sen', facts:{ field:'revolutionary', country:'China', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Sun Yat-sen was a revolutionary leader often called the 'Father of Modern China.' He was born in a village in southern China in 1866 and studied medicine before turning to politics. Sun believed that China's ancient system of emperors was holding the country back and needed to be replaced. He worked for years, often from exile, to inspire a revolution. In 1911, that revolution finally overthrew the last emperor, and China became a republic, with Sun as its first provisional president. Though China faced years of turmoil afterward, Sun Yat-sen is honored by many Chinese people as the founder of their modern nation." },

  { slug:'rani_lakshmibai', facts:{ field:'queen', country:'India', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Rani Lakshmibai was the queen of Jhansi, in India, and a fearless hero of India's fight against British rule. She was born around 1828 and was trained in riding, sword-fighting, and archery as a girl. When the British tried to take over her kingdom, she refused to give it up. During a great uprising in 1857, she led her soldiers into battle herself, sometimes riding with her young son tied to her back. She fought bravely until she was killed in combat, becoming a legend of courage. Today Rani Lakshmibai is remembered across India as a symbol of resistance and the struggle for freedom." },

  { slug:'averroes', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Spain', birthplace:'Córdoba', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Averroes was a brilliant philosopher and scholar of the medieval Islamic world. He was born in the city of Córdoba, in what is now Spain, in 1126, when it was a great center of learning under Muslim rule. Averroes was a master of many subjects, including law, medicine, and astronomy, but he is most famous for his study of philosophy. He wrote detailed commentaries on the works of the ancient Greek thinker Aristotle, helping to keep that knowledge alive. His writings were later translated into Latin and deeply influenced scholars in Christian Europe. Averroes helped connect the wisdom of the ancient world to the thinkers of the Middle Ages." },

  { slug:'shaka', facts:{ field:'king', country:'South Africa', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Shaka was a powerful king who built the Zulu people into a mighty nation in southern Africa. He was born around 1787 and had a difficult childhood before rising to become a warrior and leader. Shaka was a military genius who completely reorganized his army and invented new weapons and battle tactics. Under his leadership, the small Zulu group grew into a large and feared kingdom. His conquests reshaped the map of the region, though they also brought great upheaval and suffering. Shaka is remembered as one of the most important and formidable leaders in African history." },

  { slug:'haile_selassie', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Ethiopia', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Haile Selassie was the emperor of Ethiopia and an important figure in African history. He was born in 1892 and became emperor in 1930 of one of the few African nations never fully colonized by Europe. When the Italian army invaded his country in the 1930s, Haile Selassie made a famous speech to the League of Nations, warning the world about the dangers of ignoring aggression. He worked to modernize Ethiopia and became a symbol of African independence and unity. He also helped found the organization that grew into the African Union. To followers of the Rastafari movement, Haile Selassie holds deep religious importance." },

  { slug:'kwame_nkrumah', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'Ghana', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Kwame Nkrumah was the leader who guided Ghana to become the first African country south of the Sahara to win independence from European rule. He was born in 1909 in what was then a British colony called the Gold Coast. After studying abroad, Nkrumah returned home and led a peaceful movement demanding freedom from Britain. In 1957, his country gained independence and took the name Ghana, with Nkrumah as its first leader. He dreamed of uniting all of Africa into one strong union of nations. Kwame Nkrumah became a hero and inspiration for independence movements across the whole continent." },

  { slug:'moctezuma_ii', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Mexico', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Moctezuma II was the ruler of the powerful Aztec Empire in what is now Mexico. He was born around 1466 and led a vast empire with a magnificent capital city called Tenochtitlan, built on an island in a lake. During his reign, in 1519, Spanish explorers led by Hernán Cortés arrived, bringing horses, guns, and disease. Moctezuma first welcomed the Spanish, unsure whether they were dangerous or even divine. The Spanish took him prisoner, and he died during the fighting that followed, as his empire began to fall. The dramatic story of Moctezuma marks the tragic clash between the Aztec world and the arriving Europeans." },

  { slug:'atahualpa', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Peru', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Atahualpa was the last emperor of the great Inca Empire, which stretched along the mountains of South America. He was born around 1502 and had just won a civil war against his brother to take control of the empire. In 1532, a small band of Spanish conquistadors led by Francisco Pizarro arrived in his land. The Spanish captured Atahualpa by surprise and demanded a huge ransom of gold and silver to free him. Even after the treasure was paid, they executed him. His death helped the Spanish conquer the Inca Empire, one of the most powerful civilizations of the Americas." },

  { slug:'geronimo', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Geronimo was a leader of the Apache people who fiercely resisted the loss of his homeland. He was born around 1829 in what is now the American Southwest, in territory his people had lived on for generations. As settlers and soldiers pushed the Apache off their land, Geronimo became a bold and skillful warrior. For many years he led small groups in daring raids and escapes, evading thousands of soldiers sent to capture him. Eventually he surrendered and was held as a prisoner of war for the rest of his life. Geronimo became famous as a symbol of Native American courage and the struggle to defend a way of life." },

  { slug:'gottfried_wilhelm_leibniz', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Leipzig', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz was a German mathematician and philosopher and one of the great thinkers of his age. He was born in the city of Leipzig in 1646 and mastered many subjects, from law to science to logic. Leibniz invented calculus, a powerful branch of math for studying change and motion — at about the same time as Isaac Newton, working separately. The two men argued bitterly over who had discovered it first. Leibniz also imagined that all reasoning could one day be done by machines, an idea far ahead of his time. His notation for calculus is still the one taught in schools today." },

  { slug:'tycho_brahe', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'Denmark', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Tycho Brahe was a Danish astronomer famous for making the most accurate observations of the sky in the days before telescopes. He was born in 1546 into a noble family and was such a colorful character that he wore a metal nose after losing part of his own in a duel. Tycho built a grand observatory on an island, filled with huge, carefully made instruments. Night after night, he recorded the exact positions of the stars and planets with amazing precision. He did not fully understand what his data meant, but his assistant Johannes Kepler used it to discover how the planets move. Tycho Brahe's careful measurements helped launch the modern science of astronomy." },

  { slug:'barbara_mcclintock', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Hartford', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Barbara McClintock was an American scientist who made a groundbreaking discovery about how living things inherit traits. She was born in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1902 and devoted her life to studying the genetics of corn. By carefully observing the colorful kernels on ears of corn, McClintock discovered that some genes can actually move around, jumping to new spots on the chromosome. At first, other scientists doubted her strange-sounding idea. But decades later, her discovery of 'jumping genes' was proven correct and shown to be important for all living things. In 1983, she won the Nobel Prize, honoring years of patient, careful science." },

  { slug:'jackson_pollock', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'United States', birthplace:'Cody', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Jackson Pollock was an American painter who created a wild new style of modern art. He was born in Cody, Wyoming, in 1912 and became a leader of a movement called abstract expressionism. Instead of painting recognizable pictures, Pollock laid huge canvases on the floor and dripped, splashed, and poured paint across them. He moved his whole body as he worked, so people called his method 'action painting.' At first many people were confused or angry, wondering if it was really art at all. But his energetic, tangled paintings became famous and made Pollock one of the most influential American artists of the 20th century." },

  { slug:'edvard_munch', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Norway', work:'The Scream', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Edvard Munch was a Norwegian painter famous for showing powerful, sometimes painful emotions in his art. He was born in 1863 and suffered much loss and illness in his family, which deeply affected his work. Munch painted feelings like fear, loneliness, and love in bold, swirling colors and shapes. His most famous painting, The Scream, shows a figure on a bridge holding its face and crying out under a fiery orange sky. It has become one of the most recognized images of anxiety in all of art. Munch's honest, emotional style helped inspire a movement called expressionism." },

  { slug:'gustav_klimt', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Austria', work:'The Kiss', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Gustav Klimt was an Austrian painter famous for his dazzling, decorative art. He was born near Vienna in 1862, the son of a gold engraver, and learned to love rich patterns and shining metals. Klimt often used real gold leaf in his paintings, making them glow like jewelry. His most famous work, The Kiss, shows two lovers wrapped in shimmering golden robes covered in swirling designs. His art shocked some people of his time but delighted many others with its beauty and boldness. Today Gustav Klimt's glittering paintings are among the most popular and reproduced in the world." },

  { slug:'francis_drake', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'England', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Francis Drake was an English sailor and explorer who became a hero in England and a feared enemy of Spain. He was born around 1540 and became a bold and skillful captain during a time of rivalry between England and Spain. Between 1577 and 1580, Drake sailed all the way around the world, becoming the first Englishman to do so. Along the way he raided Spanish ships and towns for treasure, which made him rich and famous — though the Spanish considered him a pirate. Later he helped defend England against the mighty Spanish Armada in 1588. Francis Drake became a legend of the age of exploration." },

  { slug:'meriwether_lewis', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'United States', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Meriwether Lewis was an American explorer who helped lead a famous journey across the western United States. He was born in Virginia in 1774 and served as a soldier and as a secretary to President Thomas Jefferson. In 1804, Jefferson chose Lewis to lead an expedition to explore the huge territory the country had just bought in the Louisiana Purchase. Together with William Clark, and guided in part by a Shoshone woman named Sacagawea, Lewis traveled thousands of miles to the Pacific Ocean and back. The expedition mapped rivers and mountains and recorded hundreds of new plants and animals. Lewis's journey opened the American West to further exploration and settlement." },

  { slug:'friedrich_nietzsche', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Germany', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Friedrich Nietzsche was a German philosopher famous for challenging the beliefs of his time. He was born in 1844 and became a university professor while still very young. Nietzsche questioned traditional ideas about morality, religion, and truth, urging people to think boldly for themselves. He wrote in a dramatic, poetic style filled with memorable and sometimes puzzling sayings. His ideas about creating one's own values were powerful but often misunderstood, and some were later twisted by people he would have opposed. Though he suffered poor health and died out of the public eye, Nietzsche became one of the most influential and debated thinkers in modern philosophy." },

  { slug:'jean_jacques_rousseau', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Switzerland', birthplace:'Geneva', work:'The Social Contract', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Jean-Jacques Rousseau was a philosopher and writer of the Enlightenment whose ideas helped spark revolutions. He was born in the city of Geneva, in Switzerland, in 1712 and led a wandering, difficult life. Rousseau believed that people are naturally good but are corrupted by unfair societies. In his famous book The Social Contract, he argued that governments get their power from the agreement of the people, and that everyone should have a say. His ideas about freedom and equality inspired the leaders of the French Revolution. Rousseau also wrote influential works about education and nature that shaped how people thought for generations." },

  { slug:'thomas_aquinas', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Italy', work:'the Summa Theologica', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Thomas Aquinas was a philosopher and religious thinker of the Middle Ages, one of the most important in Christian history. He was born in Italy around 1225 into a noble family who wanted him to become a powerful abbot. Instead, he joined a group of poor traveling friars and devoted himself to study. Aquinas tried to show that faith and reason could work together, blending Christian belief with the logic of the ancient Greek thinker Aristotle. His enormous book, the Summa Theologica, carefully explored deep questions about God, ethics, and the universe. His ideas still shape philosophy and theology hundreds of years later." },

  { slug:'zhang_heng', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'China', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Zhang Heng was a brilliant inventor and astronomer of ancient China. He lived from 78 to 139 CE and served as an official in the court of the Han emperor. Zhang Heng studied the stars, mapped the sky, and correctly explained that the Moon shines by reflecting the light of the Sun. He is most famous for inventing an amazing device that could detect distant earthquakes. His bronze machine had dragons holding balls in their mouths, and when a faraway earthquake struck, a ball would drop to show which direction it came from. Zhang Heng's genius made him one of the greatest scientists of the ancient world." },

  { slug:'cixi', facts:{ field:'empress', country:'China', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Empress Dowager Cixi was one of the most powerful women in Chinese history. She was born in 1835 and entered the emperor's court as a young woman. After the emperor died, Cixi ruled China for nearly 50 years on behalf of young emperors, controlling the government from behind the scenes. She lived during a time when China faced growing pressure and attacks from foreign powers. Cixi is a controversial figure: some blame her for resisting reforms that might have made China stronger, while others say she skillfully held a crumbling empire together. Her long reign came near the very end of China's thousands of years of rule by emperors." },

  { slug:'hiroshige', facts:{ field:'artist', country:'Japan', birthplace:'Edo', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Hiroshige was a Japanese artist celebrated for his beautiful woodblock prints of landscapes. He was born in the city of Edo, now Tokyo, in 1797 and worked during the peaceful Edo period. Hiroshige became famous for capturing the beauty of everyday travel across Japan, showing rain, snow, mist, and moonlight in gentle, poetic scenes. His series of prints of famous places along a great highway made him hugely popular. Like his fellow artist Hokusai, his work later reached Europe and influenced painters such as Vincent van Gogh. Hiroshige is remembered as one of the last great masters of the Japanese print." },

  { slug:'hirohito', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Japan', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Hirohito was the emperor of Japan for most of the 20th century, through some of its most dramatic years. He was born in 1901 and became emperor in 1926, at a time when many Japanese saw the emperor as a living symbol of the nation. During his reign, Japan expanded aggressively and fought in World War II, ending in a terrible defeat after atomic bombs were dropped on two cities. After the war, Hirohito publicly gave up the claim that the emperor was divine and became a symbol of a new, peaceful Japan. He remained emperor as his country rebuilt into a modern, democratic nation. His long reign covered war, recovery, and remarkable change." },

  { slug:'chiang_kai_shek', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'China', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Chiang Kai-shek was a military and political leader who ruled China during decades of war and upheaval. He was born in 1887 and rose to lead the Nationalist government after the fall of China's last emperor. Chiang fought to unite the country, battled a Japanese invasion during World War II, and struggled against Communist forces led by Mao Zedong. In 1949, after losing the civil war to the Communists, Chiang and his followers fled to the island of Taiwan. There he set up a separate government that he led for many more years. Chiang Kai-shek remains an important and controversial figure in the history of both China and Taiwan." },

  { slug:'chandragupta_maurya', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'India', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Chandragupta Maurya was the founder of the first great empire to unite most of ancient India. He was born around 340 BCE and rose from humble beginnings to build a powerful kingdom. With the help of a wise adviser named Chanakya, Chandragupta overthrew a ruling dynasty and expanded his control across much of the Indian subcontinent. He created an organized government with officials, spies, and a large army to hold his vast empire together. Late in life, according to tradition, he gave up his throne to become a monk. His Maurya Empire, later ruled by his grandson Ashoka, became one of the greatest in India's history." },

  { slug:'omar_khayyam', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Persia', work:'the Rubaiyat', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Omar Khayyam was a Persian mathematician, astronomer, and poet of the Middle Ages. He was born around 1048 in what is now Iran and lived during a golden age of learning in the Islamic world. As a mathematician, Khayyam made important discoveries in algebra and helped design a remarkably accurate calendar. As an astronomer, he studied the movements of the stars and planets. But in much of the world he is best known for his poetry, collected in a book called the Rubaiyat, which reflects on life, time, and the mysteries of the world. Omar Khayyam showed how one person could excel in both science and art." },

  { slug:'sundiata_keita', facts:{ field:'king', country:'Mali', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Sundiata Keita was the founder of the great Mali Empire in West Africa. He was born in the early 1200s and, according to legend, was unable to walk as a child before rising to become a mighty warrior and leader. Sundiata united several small kingdoms and defeated a powerful rival to create the Mali Empire. He organized farming, trade, and government, helping his empire grow rich from gold and salt. His life and deeds were passed down for centuries by storytellers called griots in a famous epic. Sundiata Keita laid the foundation for the empire that would later be ruled by the fabulously wealthy Mansa Musa." },

  { slug:'pachacuti', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Peru', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Pachacuti was the ruler who transformed the Inca people into a mighty empire in the mountains of South America. He was born around 1418 and, after defending his city from invaders, began a series of conquests that greatly expanded Inca lands. Pachacuti was not only a warrior but also a great organizer and builder. He reshaped the Inca capital of Cusco and is often credited with building the famous mountain city of Machu Picchu. He created roads, storehouses, and a system for governing many different peoples. Under Pachacuti and his successors, the Inca Empire became the largest in the ancient Americas." },

  { slug:'sequoyah', facts:{ field:'scholar', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Sequoyah was a member of the Cherokee Nation who accomplished something almost no other single person in history has done: he invented a written language on his own. He was born around 1770 in what is now the American Southeast. Sequoyah could not read or write English, but he was fascinated by the way settlers used marks on paper to share information. Over many years, he created a set of symbols, called a syllabary, for the sounds of the Cherokee language. His writing system was so clever and easy to learn that thousands of Cherokee people quickly became literate. Sequoyah gave his people a powerful new tool, and giant sequoia trees are named in his honor." },

  { slug:'tecumseh', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Tecumseh was a Shawnee leader who tried to unite Native American nations to defend their lands. He was born in the Ohio country in 1768, as American settlers pushed westward onto Native lands. A brilliant speaker and warrior, Tecumseh traveled far and wide, urging different tribes to join together in a great alliance. He argued that no single tribe could sell land that belonged to all Native peoples. During the War of 1812, he allied with the British against the United States. Tecumseh was killed in battle in 1813, and his dream of a united Native confederacy ended, but his vision and courage made him a lasting hero." },

  { slug:'john_adams', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Braintree', spouse:'Abigail Adams', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"John Adams was a Founding Father and the second president of the United States. He was born in Braintree, Massachusetts, in 1735 and became a respected lawyer known for his honesty and strong principles. Adams was a leading voice for American independence and helped persuade the Continental Congress to break away from Britain. He served as a diplomat in Europe, winning vital support for the new nation. As president, he worked hard to keep the young country out of a dangerous war. He was married to Abigail Adams, whose letters to him are treasured pieces of American history. John Adams devoted his life to building the new republic." },

  { slug:'abigail_adams', facts:{ field:'first lady', country:'United States', birthplace:'Weymouth', spouse:'John Adams', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Abigail Adams was an early American first lady and one of the most remarkable women of the founding era. She was born in Weymouth, Massachusetts, in 1744 and, though she had little formal schooling, taught herself by reading widely. She was married to John Adams, the second president, and served as his closest adviser. While he was away helping create the new nation, Abigail managed the family farm and wrote him hundreds of thoughtful letters. In one famous letter, she urged him to 'remember the ladies' and not forget women's rights in the new country. Abigail Adams's wise and lively letters give us a rare window into the birth of the United States." },

  { slug:'samuel_adams', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', birthplace:'Boston', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Samuel Adams was a Founding Father who helped stir up the American Revolution. He was born in Boston in 1722 and became a fiery political leader and organizer. As Britain placed new taxes on the colonies, Adams was one of the loudest voices arguing that this was unfair. He helped organize protests, including the famous Boston Tea Party, when colonists dumped British tea into the harbor. Adams was skilled at rallying ordinary people to the cause of liberty through speeches and writings. His energetic organizing helped push the colonies toward declaring independence, earning him a place among the boldest patriots of his time." },

  { slug:'john_marshall', facts:{ field:'judge', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"John Marshall was the most important Chief Justice in the history of the United States Supreme Court. He was born in Virginia in 1755 and served as a soldier in the Revolutionary War before becoming a lawyer. Appointed to lead the Supreme Court in 1801, Marshall served for 34 years, longer than anyone else. He established the idea that the Court can decide whether laws follow the Constitution, a power called judicial review. Through his careful decisions, Marshall made the Supreme Court a strong and equal branch of government. His work shaped the way American law and government still function today." },

  { slug:'james_monroe', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Virginia', work:'the Monroe Doctrine', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"James Monroe was the fifth president of the United States and the last of the founding generation to hold the office. He was born in Virginia in 1758 and fought as a young soldier in the Revolutionary War. Monroe served the new country in many roles, including as a diplomat who helped arrange the Louisiana Purchase. As president, his time in office was so calm and hopeful that it was called the 'Era of Good Feelings.' He is best remembered for the Monroe Doctrine, a bold policy warning European powers not to interfere in the Americas. Monroe helped guide the young nation as it grew in size and confidence." },

  { slug:'andrew_jackson', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Andrew Jackson was the seventh president of the United States and one of the most forceful and divisive. He was born in 1767 in the Carolinas and rose to fame as a tough general and war hero. Jackson presented himself as a champion of the 'common man' and was hugely popular with many ordinary voters. But his presidency also had a dark side: he supported the forced removal of Native American nations from their homelands. This cruel policy led to the deadly journey known as the Trail of Tears, on which thousands of Native people died. Andrew Jackson remains a powerful but deeply controversial figure in American history." },

  { slug:'nikolaus_otto', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'Germany', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Nikolaus Otto was a German inventor whose work helped make the modern automobile possible. He was born in 1832 and, though he had little formal training as an engineer, he was fascinated by engines. In 1876, Otto built the first practical engine that burned fuel inside itself in a repeating four-step cycle — intake, compression, power, and exhaust. This 'four-stroke' design was reliable, efficient, and small enough to be useful in many machines. It became the foundation for the engines that would soon power cars, trucks, and countless other vehicles. The basic cycle Otto perfected is still used in most gasoline engines on the road today." },

  { slug:'dolley_madison', facts:{ field:'first lady', country:'United States', spouse:'James Madison', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Dolley Madison was one of the most beloved and influential first ladies in American history. She was born in 1768 and was married to James Madison, the fourth president of the United States. Dolley was famous for her warmth, charm, and skill at bringing people together, and she helped define what the role of first lady could be. Her most celebrated moment came during the War of 1812: as British troops advanced on Washington to burn the White House, she refused to flee until a famous portrait of George Washington was saved. Dolley Madison's courage and grace made her a national symbol of the young republic." },

  { slug:'henry_clay', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Henry Clay was one of the most important American politicians of the 1800s, known as 'the Great Compromiser.' He was born in Virginia in 1777 and became a powerful leader in Congress. During his long career, Clay ran for president several times but never won, yet his influence was enormous. As the nation argued bitterly over slavery, Clay worked to craft compromises that held the country together and delayed civil war for decades. He believed deeply in the Union and in a plan to strengthen the American economy. Henry Clay's skill at finding middle ground made him a legend of American politics." },

  { slug:'daniel_webster', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Daniel Webster was one of the greatest speakers and statesmen in American history. He was born in New Hampshire in 1782 and became famous as a lawyer, senator, and defender of the Union. Webster was known for his powerful, thundering speeches, which could hold audiences spellbound for hours. As the nation grew divided over slavery and states' rights, he argued forcefully that the United States must remain one country. His words 'Liberty and Union, now and forever, one and inseparable' became famous. Along with Henry Clay, Daniel Webster worked to hold the nation together in the tense years before the Civil War." },

  { slug:'john_c_calhoun', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"John C. Calhoun was a powerful and controversial American statesman from South Carolina. He was born in 1782 and served in many high offices, including as vice president. Calhoun was a brilliant thinker, but he used his talents to defend slavery and the interests of the Southern states. He argued that individual states could reject federal laws they disagreed with, an idea called nullification that threatened to break the country apart. He also claimed that slavery was a 'positive good,' a view later generations rightly condemned. John C. Calhoun's ideas about states' rights helped push the nation toward the Civil War." },

  { slug:'ulysses_s_grant', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Ulysses S. Grant was the general who led the Union to victory in the Civil War and later became president. He was born in Ohio in 1822 and struggled in business before the war gave him a chance to show his talents. As commander of the Union armies, Grant was determined and relentless, and his leadership helped end slavery by defeating the Confederacy. When the war ended, he offered generous terms to the surrendering soldiers. As the eighteenth president, Grant worked to protect the rights of newly freed Black Americans during the difficult years of Reconstruction. Ulysses S. Grant is remembered as one of the nation's most important military leaders." },

  { slug:'robert_e_lee', facts:{ field:'general', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Robert E. Lee was the most famous general of the Confederate side in the American Civil War. He was born in Virginia in 1807 into a distinguished family and became a respected officer in the United States Army. When the Civil War began, Lee made the fateful choice to lead the armies of the Confederacy, the states fighting to preserve slavery. He was a skilled commander who won several battles against larger forces. But he was finally defeated by Ulysses S. Grant and surrendered in 1865. Robert E. Lee remains a deeply controversial figure, admired by some for his military skill but criticized for fighting to defend slavery." },

  { slug:'william_lloyd_garrison', facts:{ field:'reformer', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"William Lloyd Garrison was one of the most passionate voices against slavery in American history. He was born in Massachusetts in 1805 and became a fearless newspaper editor and reformer. In 1831, he founded an anti-slavery newspaper called The Liberator, in which he demanded the immediate and complete end of slavery. Garrison's words were bold and uncompromising, and they angered many people, even putting his life in danger. He helped build a nationwide movement of abolitionists who worked to end the cruel practice. William Lloyd Garrison's tireless writing and speaking helped turn public opinion against slavery in the years before the Civil War." },

  { slug:'harriet_beecher_stowe', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', work:'Uncle Tom\'s Cabin', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Harriet Beecher Stowe was an American writer whose novel helped change how the nation thought about slavery. She was born in Connecticut in 1811 into a family of preachers and reformers. Deeply troubled by the cruelty of slavery, Stowe wrote a novel called Uncle Tom's Cabin, published in 1852. The book told the emotional story of enslaved people and their suffering, and it became a huge bestseller across the North. It moved countless readers to oppose slavery and stirred fierce anger in the South. According to legend, President Lincoln called her 'the little lady who started this great war.' Harriet Beecher Stowe showed the power of a story to change hearts." },

  { slug:'elizabeth_cady_stanton', facts:{ field:'reformer', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Elizabeth Cady Stanton was a founding leader of the movement for women's rights in the United States. She was born in New York in 1815 and grew frustrated by the many rights that women were denied. In 1848, she helped organize the Seneca Falls Convention, the first major gathering for women's rights in America. There she wrote a bold declaration stating that 'all men and women are created equal.' Stanton spent her life fighting for a woman's right to vote, to own property, and to be treated as an equal. Though she did not live to see women win the vote, Elizabeth Cady Stanton laid the foundation for that victory." },

  { slug:'lucretia_mott', facts:{ field:'reformer', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Lucretia Mott was an American reformer who fought against both slavery and the unfair treatment of women. She was born in 1793 and became a Quaker preacher known for her powerful speaking. Mott worked tirelessly as an abolitionist, opening her home to people escaping slavery and speaking out against injustice. She was also a pioneer for women's rights, helping to organize the Seneca Falls Convention in 1848 alongside Elizabeth Cady Stanton. Calm, brave, and deeply principled, Mott inspired younger reformers to keep fighting for equality. Lucretia Mott showed how one determined person could stand up for many different causes of justice." },

  { slug:'dolores_huerta', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Dawson', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Dolores Huerta is an American activist who has spent her life fighting for the rights of farm workers. She was born in Dawson, New Mexico, in 1930 and saw how hard and unfair life was for the people who harvested the nation's food. Together with Cesar Chavez, she co-founded a union to help farm workers win better pay and safer conditions. Huerta was a brilliant organizer and negotiator, and she created the famous rallying cry 'Sí, se puede' — 'Yes, we can.' She faced arrests and danger but never gave up. Dolores Huerta remains a celebrated champion of workers, women, and immigrants." },

  { slug:'bayard_rustin', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Bayard Rustin was a brilliant organizer behind the scenes of the American civil rights movement. He was born in Pennsylvania in 1912 and became a champion of nonviolent protest, inspired by the teachings of Mahatma Gandhi. Rustin taught these methods to Martin Luther King Jr. and helped shape the movement's peaceful strategy. His greatest achievement was organizing the enormous 1963 March on Washington, where King gave his famous 'I Have a Dream' speech. Because of prejudice against him, Rustin often worked out of the spotlight, but his skill was essential to the movement's success. Bayard Rustin is now honored as one of its unsung heroes." },

  { slug:'coretta_scott_king', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', spouse:'Martin Luther King Jr.', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Coretta Scott King was a civil rights leader who fought for justice for her whole life. She was born in Alabama in 1927 and studied music before joining the struggle for equality. She was married to Martin Luther King Jr. and stood beside him through the dangerous years of the civil rights movement. After he was assassinated in 1968, Coretta carried on his work with courage and dignity. She worked to make his birthday a national holiday and founded a center to teach his methods of nonviolence. Coretta Scott King became a respected leader in her own right, championing peace, equality, and human rights around the world." },

  { slug:'betty_friedan', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', work:'The Feminine Mystique', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Betty Friedan was a writer and activist who helped launch a new wave of the women's rights movement. She was born in Illinois in 1921 and became a journalist. In 1963, she published a book called The Feminine Mystique, which gave voice to the frustration many women felt when they were expected to find happiness only as homemakers. The book became a bestseller and started a national conversation. Friedan went on to help found a major organization to fight for women's equality in jobs, education, and the law. Betty Friedan's work helped open new opportunities for women across the United States." },

  { slug:'phyllis_schlafly', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Phyllis Schlafly was an American activist known as a powerful voice for conservative causes. She was born in Missouri in 1924 and became a skilled writer, speaker, and political organizer. In the 1970s, she led a famous campaign against a proposed constitutional amendment on women's rights, arguing that it would harm traditional family life. Her energetic organizing helped stop the amendment, surprising many observers. Schlafly showed how ordinary citizens could shape national politics through grassroots effort. Though many strongly disagreed with her views, Phyllis Schlafly became one of the most influential conservative activists of her era, demonstrating the passionate debates of American democracy." },

  { slug:'cesar_rodney', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Cesar Rodney was a Founding Father remembered for a dramatic midnight ride to help declare American independence. He was born in Delaware in 1728 and served his colony as a leader and lawmaker. In July 1776, the delegates from Delaware were split on whether to vote for independence, and Rodney's vote was needed to break the tie. Though he was ill and far from Philadelphia, Rodney rode all night through a thunderstorm to reach the Continental Congress in time. His vote helped Delaware support the Declaration of Independence. Cesar Rodney's determined ride made him a hero of the American Revolution." },

  { slug:'roger_sherman', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Roger Sherman was a Founding Father who helped shape the government of the United States. He was born in Massachusetts in 1721 and rose from working as a shoemaker to become a respected lawyer and statesman. Sherman is the only person to sign all four of the great documents of the founding era, including the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution. At the Constitutional Convention, he proposed a famous solution called the Great Compromise. It settled a bitter dispute by creating a Congress with two houses: one based on population and one giving every state equal votes. Roger Sherman's clever compromise made the Constitution possible." },

  { slug:'john_jay', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"John Jay was a Founding Father who served the young United States in many important roles. He was born in New York in 1745 and became a lawyer and leader during the Revolution. Jay helped negotiate the peace treaty with Britain that officially ended the Revolutionary War. He also wrote several of the Federalist Papers, essays that helped convince Americans to approve the new Constitution. President George Washington then appointed him the very first Chief Justice of the United States, helping to establish the Supreme Court. John Jay's steady service in diplomacy, writing, and law helped guide the nation through its earliest years." },

  { slug:'warren_g_harding', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Warren G. Harding was the twenty-ninth president of the United States, whose time in office is a cautionary tale. He was born in Ohio in 1865 and worked as a newspaper publisher before entering politics. Harding won the presidency in 1920 by promising a 'return to normalcy' after the hardships of World War I, and he was very popular with voters. But he trusted the wrong people, and several men he appointed became involved in serious corruption scandals. Harding died suddenly while still in office, before the worst scandals came fully to light. Warren G. Harding's presidency is often remembered as a warning about the importance of honest government." },

  { slug:'woodrow_wilson', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Woodrow Wilson was the twenty-eighth president of the United States, who led the nation through World War I. He was born in Virginia in 1856 and worked as a college professor and university president before entering politics. As president, Wilson tried to keep America out of the war in Europe, but eventually led the country into the fight. After the war, he proposed a bold plan for lasting peace, including a League of Nations where countries could settle disputes. He won the Nobel Peace Prize for these efforts, though the United States never joined the League. Wilson's record is mixed: he championed peace abroad but supported segregation at home." },

  { slug:'dwight_d_eisenhower', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Dwight D. Eisenhower was a great general who became the thirty-fourth president of the United States. He was born in Texas in 1890 and rose through the army to command the Allied forces in Europe during World War II. He planned and led the massive D-Day invasion in 1944 that helped defeat Nazi Germany. After the war, 'Ike' was so admired that he was elected president in 1952. As president, he helped build the interstate highway system and worked to keep the peace during the tense years of the Cold War. He also sent troops to protect Black students integrating a school. Dwight D. Eisenhower was trusted as a steady, experienced leader." },

  { slug:'lyndon_b_johnson', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Lyndon B. Johnson was the thirty-sixth president of the United States, who pushed through major laws for equality. He was born in Texas in 1908 and became a masterful politician known for his skill at persuading Congress. He became president suddenly in 1963 after the assassination of John F. Kennedy. Johnson used his political talent to pass the landmark Civil Rights Act and Voting Rights Act, which struck down unjust laws against Black Americans. He also launched programs to fight poverty. But his presidency was overshadowed by the unpopular Vietnam War, which divided the country. Lyndon B. Johnson's record combines great achievements at home with a costly war abroad." },

  { slug:'richard_nixon', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Richard Nixon was the thirty-seventh president of the United States and the only one ever to resign from office. He was born in California in 1913 and had a long career in politics before becoming president in 1969. Nixon achieved important things, including opening relations with China and reducing tensions with the Soviet Union. But his presidency collapsed under the Watergate scandal, when it was revealed that he had covered up illegal activities to help his re-election. Facing removal from office, Nixon resigned in 1974. His downfall showed that in the United States, not even a president is above the law." },

  { slug:'ronald_reagan', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Ronald Reagan was the fortieth president of the United States and one of the most influential of the 20th century. He was born in Illinois in 1911 and worked as a Hollywood actor before turning to politics. Known as 'the Great Communicator,' Reagan was famous for his warm, confident speaking style. As president in the 1980s, he cut taxes and championed conservative ideas about smaller government. On the world stage, he took a firm stand against the Soviet Union, yet also worked with its leader to reduce nuclear weapons. His presidency is often linked to the peaceful end of the Cold War. Ronald Reagan reshaped American politics for a generation." },

  { slug:'sandra_day_o_connor', facts:{ field:'judge', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Sandra Day O'Connor made history as the first woman ever to serve on the United States Supreme Court. She was born in Texas in 1930 and grew up on a remote cattle ranch in Arizona. Despite graduating near the top of her law school class, she struggled to find work because law firms rarely hired women at the time. She built her career in Arizona and became a respected judge. In 1981, President Ronald Reagan appointed her to the Supreme Court, breaking a barrier that had stood for nearly 200 years. Known for her careful, independent judgment, O'Connor often cast the deciding vote in important cases. Sandra Day O'Connor opened the door for women in the highest levels of American law." },
];
